animal.description:
BONDED WITH ZOEY 
Maya is bonded with Zoey, 6 year old white lab mix, and they are looking for a home that can keep them together.

Meet Maya!

Maya enjoys living life in the slow lane. She's a calm and easy-going girl at just needs a couch to rest on. She loves hanging out in the play yard and going on walks with her fur-sibling, Zoey. Maya is still adjusting to life at Alaqua, and it's taking her some time to fully decompress and let her personality truly shine. 

Maya's ideal home is a relaxed environment where she can be spoiled like the princess she is. She needs a family that has lots of patience and will take the time to help her come out of her shell and gain confidence. She would benefit going home with her fur-sibling, Zoey, or having another dog in the home that can help her quickly become comfortable. As long as the other fur sibling is not a cat; she has lived with one before and prefers dog siblings only. Maya can't wait to meet you and find her forever home!

animal.description:
BONDED WITH MAYA 
Zoey is bonded with Maya, a black lab mix, and they are looking for a home that can adopt them both so they can stay together.

Zoey enjoys living the relaxed life and not letting much bother her. She is sweet as pie and gets along with everyone. She is soft spoken and is a little reserved at first and, but give her a couple treats and she will warm right up to you. She loves running around in the play yard with her buddy Maya. They are like two peas in a pod! 

She is working on coming out of her shell. She is nervous in load upbeat environments and would benefit being in a home with a low key atmosphere. She has been in a home with cats and found out she does not like living with them. Her dream is to be in a home that will allow her to have the best of both worlds; plenty of exercise and days chilling on the couch. Zoey is eager to meet you and cannot wait to find her forever family!

Want to bring me home? It's easy! All you have to do is fill out an application on our website: acadianaanimalaid.org/adopt/dog-adoption/application

We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

animal.description: Buddy is an 8 year old neutered male Labrador Retriever mix. He likes to play and roll around in the snow. He loves the outdoors and enjoys running after balls or toys. He has a history of being abused by previous owners so it takes him a little to open up. He has a tendency to bark at people he doesn't know, usually he wags his tail when barking because he's excited for the attention but unsure about the person. He has no bite history and has been around children before with no problems. He has been around large dogs before but has never been around small dogs. He hasn't had any direct contact with cats so he has no experience being around them alone but also hasn't shown any aggression towards a cat. He's capable of adapting with a TLC and warms up with a little love and care. He appears to be in good health but has a small lipoma on his belly. He's had a hard life and needs a good home that will give him lots of love and make the rest of his life a happy one.  If you would like more information about Buddy, please contact Bonnie at purplecookiex@aol.com.

animal.description:
Cyrus is a pittie mix, he is around 72 lbs., and 3 yrs. old. When Cyrus came into rescue he had a broken leg that required his back leg to be amputated. Don’t worry, it doesn’t slow him down! 

Please read all about Cyrus (below) and if you feel you are a good match for him and want to meet him, please complete an application found on our website, we will be adopting Cyrus into the Portland area. Videos of him are in the comments. www.mywayhomedogrescue.org

Cyrus is a mellow guy but always wakes up excited to greet each day! Once he zooms around the yard he is a great leash walker with minimal pull (front clip harness works great too). Due to his surgery he has spent a lot of crate time and has no problem coming in after a walk to head for his crate for a nap with his pillow. 

Cryus is house trained and no matter the circumstance has never had an accident in the house. He will whine to let you know he needs to go outside. He is not much of a barker, likes people and other dogs. He is not a dog park dog. His injury is healing and he would not feel comfortable being tossed into a dog park. Cyrus will chase cats and small animals- no cats for this boy.

His perfect home would have a person to continue his training (he has come so far). He needs a secure yard to do his zoomies. He doesn’t mind being left at home if you need to go out. He loves car rides. He would be fine as an only dog but has found comfort with his foster brothers and sisters. He is a funny guy, he gets excited to go out and is just as excited to come back in. We think he is a couch potato that does zoomies. 

Cyrus has had his vaccinations, heart wormed tested, has been neutered, de-wormed, flea/tick treatment and microchipped.  His adoption fee is $350.

My Way Home adopts in the Portland metro area only.

animal.description: Please contact Vivienne (viviennejames@comcast.net) for more information about this pet.Meet Rascal. He is an 11 year old chihuahua who weighs 12 lbs. He is a great little boy who likes to talk. That is all he is doing but his talking is often mistaken for growling. That is how Rascal communicates. He loves to be petted and will growl the entire time you are petting. Stop and he moves closer all the while he is growling. He never bites but obviously the growling does take a little while to get used to. On a positive note, Rascal is a very social guy. He gets along well with all his foster brothers and sisters. He is even good with the foster kitties. He likes to run and play and hang out but he is truly about being next to you to be petted. Rascal walks well on a leash and likes to ride in the car. He is a great little guy. He just needs the right person to give him and chance and continue the love he has received from his foster mom. Rascal is neutered, current on all his shots and microchipped. To be considered for his forever family please contact Vivienne at viviennejames@comcast.net. APPROVED APPLICATION AND ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED.

animal.description: Jemison is the sweetest and most beautiful boy weighing in at approximately 100lbs. He is estimated at 2 years old, and we think his name fits him perfectly because he is just a Jem (Gem)! He was rescued from the South Korean dog meat industry to give him a chance to live a normal dog life. Jemison is very puppy like in his play and enjoys his time out of kennel, showing off his favorite stuffed toys to anyone he sees. Although stuffed toys are his absolute favorite, he also enjoys busy bones, Nyla bones, Kongs, and rope toys (he is so talented...he can hold two toys at once!). His favorite part of the day is enrichment time! He is a social boy and is easily leashed, and walks well! Despite his size, he is a gentle giant, and takes treats so sweetly! Jemison would do best in a home without other dogs as he is still learning how to be appropriate with them. Our precious jemstone is looking to be the diamond of someone's heart, and is looking to find his forever home that will love every bit of his puppy love! Jemison is currently living at an offsite location. If you are interested in adding Jemison to your family, please fill out the application (https://bit.ly/2M27kgo) and submit it to rcorkrin@hswcmd.org. Your application will then be reviewed and you will be contacted if you and Jemison seem to be a good match to set up a meet and greet!

animal.description: Jake and Jewel are a bonded pair who we would like a home where they can continue to grow together. Both were rescued from the South Korean dog meat industry to give them a chance to live a normal dog life. They are both smaller in size, Jake is about 30lbs and Jewel is 25lbs. Jake has a bit more confidence and is showing Jewel how to trust the people around them. Jake and Jewel will often investigate novel toys and treats when no one is watching...but they've been caught in the act of enjoying what has been offered! Jake is beginning to come out of his shell a bit more than Jewel but they are both starting to show interest in enrichment and toys. They still have a ways to go before walking on leash but can easily be transported in their crates to new areas. They are incredibly adorable and searching for a family with a lot of love and patience to help them continue to grow into confident dogs. It has been exciting to watch them slowly take interest in what their staff and volunteers are doing around them! animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi Everyone! My name is Monzie and I'm a big love dog!

Animal Allies of Texas rescued me and I'm living in a foster home with two teenage girls and a female Boston Terrier. I like running around in the backyard. I am 100% house-trained and I love sleeping on my dog bed. I don't chew on anything I'm not supposed to. I have some toys, and I'm learning how to play with them.

I'm a smart boy, but I'm not an alpha dog. My foster parents are good at helping me overcome some fear issues... sometimes I flinch at sudden movements or loud noises. My foster Mom was a little worried about hosting a Pitbull, but now we're best friends and I follow her everywhere. I am extremely gentle and loving. There's nothing I like better than hugs and being close to people. I love giving kisses and putting my head in your lap. I don't display any food aggression, people aggression or dog aggression. I haven't been around cats so I don't know ho I'd act around them. My foster family says I am very quiet and I never bark. I know how to shake hands and I respond well to treats and positive reinforcement.

I do well in the car. I have a crate, but my foster family trusts me when they leave for short periods so they let me stay out. Mostly I like to lounge around on my bed or my blankie. If you let dogs on the couch I am totally on board, although my foster family is teaching me not to get on the people furniture. I do well on the leash and enjoy walking around the neighborhood or at the park.

My foster family says my fur is super-soft and I hardly shed. They also say I have a big head and big feet. I guess they match the size of my heart! They think I would be an incredible companion dog for the right person or family. I really am a big, goofy, lazy lapdog who just needs lots of love.

The only thing I need to complete my perfect life is a forever home. If you would like to meet me please contact AAT (Animal Allies of Texas). I'd sure love to meet you!

And if you would like to volunteer to same more lives and foster cats or dogs, please go to the Animal Allies of Texas website and inquire. It is wasn't for the kind lady who sprung me from the shelter, I would not be here to tell my story. AAT will educate you on what it takes to be a foster parent.

Meet ZEKE.  He is a young Lab-Pit mix and is a nice medium size. He walks fairly well on the leash. He is curious, but calm. He's a bit shy.  He isn't a ball of active energy & that’s not a bad thing! He loves attention and will likely greet you at his kennel door to look at you with those soulful eyes of his. 

We think he’d adore being a pampered indoor companion who’d love lots of snuggling.  He will need some basic training (as all dogs do), but I get the sense that he is a smart boy who will settle in with you and be eager to learn and please you. 

ZEKE is sponsored!! That means his fully vetted adoption fee is only $50.   Come visit him Tuesday - Saturday 11AM - 3PM. No appointments necessary, but please bring your masks to wear indoors or outside if in close proximity to others.

*****
If don't have room in your home but do have room in your heart, you can help one of our homeless pets find a home of its own by sponsoring them. By sponsoring, you will be paying part of the adoption fee, making it possible for them to be adopted much sooner. 
            
For Adoption or Sponsorship  Information please call 270-586-3125.  
ADOPTION HOURS:  Tuesday - Saturday 11 am to 3 pm Central Time. Adoption Fee for our dogs is $95.  All dogs will be adopted fully vetted.  Spay/Neuter.  Wormed. Please go to www.yvpr.org/adoptions for more information and to complete an adoption application. 
Tiny is a 2 year old neutered male Chi/Boston Terrier mix. He has mostly Brindle with white on his neck and chest.  He and his 2 sibling brothers, T-Bone and Tiger are looking for their forever homes.  Owners are now living in a place that they are over the limit with their dogs.  They are all loved so much.  Tiny is UTD on his vaccinations.
Tiny is the one that loves the deepest out of the 3!  He LOVES laps and is playful and loves to play fetch!  If you say, “Go Tiny go”, he will keep going in laps or circles.  He is leash trained and house trained.  He knows the commands sit (with the snapping of fingers), stay & lay.  He is an inside dog but loves to roam in his fenced in yard in the summer.  He is free fed.  He has been exposed to Boxers (large dogs) and other chihuahuas and does fine.  He will chase cats if they run from him and that has happened in outdoor settings only.  He has been around newborn to 8 years of age but Tiny seems to respond well to mature children.
Owners would love to see this trio adopted together but knows that would be a unique situation.  They would just be happy knowing they were in a loving home. 
Does Tiny sound like the buddy you have been looking for?
An application must be filled out and accepted before a meet can be set up. If accepted, you will hear from us within 72 hours. You will have the opportunity to ask questions before you meet the pet; an adoption may or may not happen at that time. We do adopt outside the Yakima area IF you are able to come to Yakima to pick up your adopted pet.  We do not have a kennel facility; all of our pets are in foster homes. Therefore, meets and adoptions take place at either our office or at a place chosen by the foster.   If a pet has 'pending' beside its name, an adoption is imminent. Please fill out an application anyway because adoptions don't always go through. Your application will be kept on file for 30 days in case you find another pet you'd like to apply for.  Thanks for thinking adoption and Good Luck!

animal.description:
Want a side of meatball with your spaghetti? Rumple will do! I am 5-8 years old and a potbellied pig. Okay, so not really, but look at me! I even snort! I came in as a stray a few days before Christmas. I was in bad shape, my ears were so swollen and infected. After receiving all the good medical care I needed, I am ready for adoption. I do need continued medication for my skin, which is looking amazing these days. I am a happy guy that walks great on leash and the cutest sight is when I get the zoomies. I am sensitive to some handling, mainly because I was in some pain when I came in and still can be unsure of certain handling. I also get a little grabby for my snacks and toys, so kids over 8 years old is best for me. I love toys, squeaky rubber balls especially! I will keep myself entertained and don’t mind if you join in on the fun. I will need a feline free home. I am hard to redirect and I seem to want to chase the kitties. I did not mind the other dog I met here and I think I would do fine with a dog friend at home.

Medical:  Rumple is currently receiving treatment for severe ear infections in both of his ears.  He received a long acting medication in both of his ears on 12/28.  This medication is waxy and yellow in color and will last for 30 days.

During his time at HSHA, Rumple was found to suffer from chronic ear infections.  It is possible that he may develop more infections in the future.  Chronic ear infections can result in permanent changes to the ear canal that make them more prone to developing future infections.  Ear infections can be uncomfortable and require veterinary treatment.  Rumple should be seen as soon as possible by your regular veterinarian should he start to show signs of infection (ex: head shaking, scratching at ears, swollen ear flap, ear debris).  Your veterinarian may recommend diagnostic testing and surgical options.

animal.description:
Trixie, female, 40 lbs, 4yrs,
-must go to an adult only home as she is very clingy to her human Dad doesn't want to share him, gets along with her dog sibling, does well on walks but some dogs get her excited while other dogs she totally ignores, loves chasing squirrels, has medium level energy, she gets a long walk, sometimes jogging, in the mornings and then she plays with her housemate in the evening in the yard, doesn't play fetch so unless it's a walk or playing with our other dog she just watches the traffic out front or sleeps, she's pretty good on leash so would do well if someone wants to walk a lot for exercise,  I walk her and another 50+ lb dog with a baby in a stroller and have no problems controlling them, can be left home without crating, smart and food driven, content sleeping in a ball or watching us do different activities, gets excited and greets me when I get home, has a drive for food and will steal it from her house mate or even our daughter's hand, but isn't aggressive if you take her food away, is pretty good about going to her "place" and staying quietly, but I reinforce with food, so that helps considerably,  good about sticking around in the yard if the gate gets left open or she goes out to greet someone, but if a loud car or motorcycle drives by her instinct is to chase and bark so she'll bolt.  
She also loves to chase squirrels in the yard, but is pretty good about not chasing on a walk, unless the squirrels are chasing each other and chattering near her, then she gets excited. She isn't real "snuggly", but wants to always lay next to me or near me, will follow me to different rooms and lay nearby, definitely has a herding/shepherd mentality that she keeps an eye on things and lets others know she doesn't approve, an incredibly loud bark for her size. 


Requirements for Adoption:
Sorry but we only place our dogs in the Columbus area.  For rescues/shelters across Ohio, visit:  ColumbusDogConnection.com/RescuesShelters.html
Must be over the age of 24 to adopt.
Your resident pets must be spayed/neutered.

Adoption Process:
We do not have an application. Adoptions are pet-adopter driven.
To meet our pets:
Call our office at 614-471-9000 or click on the pet which you are interested in and send email. We will be happy to discuss the adoption process with you and set-up a visit at time of contact. The foster dogs are in foster homes and most of the cats reside at our office.

The adoption process includes a lease manager reference (if applicable) , a veterinarian reference, a home-visit (in-person or virtual).
If you've never owned a pet, part of our adoption process requires that you call several vet offices to compare services, prices, and availability. 
Questions to ask include:
How many doctors are at your practice?
Can I request to see a specific Vet or would I be scheduled with first available?
What are your hours?
How much is:   annual exam, heartworm test & tablets, an x-ray,  vaccines, a non-emergency office call? 
Do you recommend vaccines every year or every three years?  (every 3 yrs as suggested by the AVMA)           

The pooches that visit your home will not be left there at the end of the visit. We take them back home with us so your family can discuss to ensure he/she is a good fit for your home.

There is an adoption agreement and adoption fees as follows:
 $300 for Adult Dogs (6yrs  & younger)
 $200 for Senior Dogs (7 yrs and older)
 $80 for Cats  

 All pets are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm tested (dogs), fiv/leukemia tested (cats), & micro-chipped.
Known medical conditions are discussed at time of inquiry.

animal.description:
Max is a special boy in need of a special home. Max was adopted from us 6 years ago as a puppy. Unfortunatly, Max's owner became very ill and was no longer able to care for him. Max was removed from his home and surrendered by extended family to animal control. He was brought back to us in hopes of finding him a new, loving, forever home. Max is understandably heartbroken and very confused. He wants nothing more then to be with someone at all times. He finds comfort in companionship and long walks. Max is very nervous being back at the shelter and does take some time to warm up to new people. Once he trusts you, he's a giant love bug. Max is overweight and will require a home with a family who can help him get back down to and maintain a healthy weight. This big boy is entering his golden years and deserves to spend them in the comfort of a new, quiet forever home. We are unsure of how Max is with other animals, but have been told he would prefer to be an only pet.

To view the adoptable dogs at our shelter, you must fill out an adoption application found on our website. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, we are showing dogs on an appointment only basis. Please understand that we are receiving a high volume of applications at this time and are doing our best to address as many as we can. Please be patient. Thank you.

The adoption fee for adult dogs is $250. Aside from the shelter, food and water, exercise and compassion they receive while in our care, this also includes veterinary services such as Rabies, Distemper+Lepto, Bordetella, H3N2/H3N8 Influenza, heartworm testing, fecal exams, preventions and deworming medications. Spays/Neuters are also included as part of the adoption fee as is microchipping. 
Puppies under the age of 6 months have an adoption fee of $350. The veterinary services rendered include puppies first round of vaccines, fecal exams, deworming medications, preventions, and microchipping. Our facility spays and neuters dogs at 6 months of age. If the puppy is adopted prior to his, or her prescheduled surgery date, a $200 spay/neuter deposit will be taken on the day of adoption. This deposit it refundable and will be returned to the adopter once proof of the procedure is returned to the shelter. 
COVID-19 NOTE: Please understand that we are looking for forever home for our pets. We understand that many people have a lot of time on their hands during the COVID-19 pandemic, so this may seem like an ideal time to bring home a new pet. Please be sure you are prepared to give your new pet his, or her forever home once our lives go back to normal. They deserve it. Thank you and stay safe.

animal.description:
This very handsome young boy is Jet and he is looking for a kind family to give him the life every dog deserves. We found out about Jet on Thanksgiving when a girl travelled to meet her boyfriend's family and she was told Jet was going to be euthanized. Kindly, she contacted rescue for help for him and we are so thankful she did. Jet was purchased as a puppy and left to roam. He was hit by a car and sadly both of his front legs were broken. A vet set them in splints and soon, Jet was able to walk again. His owners lost their home and one of them died so poor Jet was left tied to a tree, ignored and neglected with no shelter at all. All he could do was bark at people walking by, pleading for help. The owner's wife contacted a shelter to take him, but they were too full so they decided to have him euthanized instead. So Jet was able to come to rescue in the nick of time. Since Jet has arrived to rescue, he is a completely different dog! He is flourishing here, has made new friends and is doing so well. He is now fully vetted and ready for a new chapter in his life with a family who will never abandon him again. Jet may be a bit nervous trying new things, but he is doing well and is eager to learn. He would do great with an experienced family who knows the breed and can continue working with him. He'll need a fenced in yard and would do well with another canine companion to show him the ropes. While we are all so sorry Jet had such an awful start in life, we can’t wait to see him happy in a great home of his own with a family who loves him - he deserves so much better than he has known so far!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Penny is an adorable and loving (almost) 4 month old shepherd puppy.  She has mastered the doggy door and loves her foster brother Rocky, 125lb shepherd, the MOST.

PLEASE NOTE:  Penny is mostly a normal puppy... but has been classified with megaesophagus.  This is a condition in which the esophagus is wider than normal, and special feeding/limited diet is required. In Penny's case she eats with her paws up on a crate, which allows the food to pass easier by gravity.  A Bailey chair has been ordered and she will be trained to use it.  One thing that is helpful... Penny is open to everything we do to help her!  She's a wonderful puppy, a very smart girl, and learns quickly without stubbornness.  Penny is also a love, and she enjoys cuddling on laps or in arms.

For more information on her condition: http://caninemegaesophagusinfo.com/

To donate to her ongoing medical care and to purchase a Bailey chair, donations can be made through our main website: www.centralcoastspca.org

Our hours for adoption are Monday to Friday from 11:00 am - 5:30 pm

Animal Services is closed on statutory holidays.

BACKGROUND
Almost all the dogs at Animal Services are picked up as strays running loose on the streets of Winnipeg and therefore they come to us with no known history. For this reason, we are not sure how they will interact with other dogs, cats or how they are with children. We would suggest that if you have younger children you bring them down with you to meet the dogs. We also have an outdoor play area where we can do introductions with any other dogs that live in the home.

All locally adopted dogs come with a 7 day home trial. If you return the dog within this time period, you will be refunded your adoption fee less the non-refundable deposit.

Please feel free to meet all the dogs and puppies outside of their kennels, just let the kennel attendants know that you would like a meet and greet with the dog outside of his pen. The dogs are much more relaxed when outside of their kennels. They would love to meet you!

Name: Wilbur
Nicknames: Wilby. Porky. Silly butt. Snuggle butt. Willllllbur.
Breed: Olde English Bulldog
Age: 2 Years
Sex: Male
Weight: 50 lbs. 
Before OMD: Surrendered to us by his owner due to significant life changes. 
Energy Level: Medium-high. He isn’t your stereotypical couch potato Bulldog. He loves to sleep but he’s also all about his walks and zoomies.
Smart Cookie Level: He knows sit and he’s happy to give his paw but to be honest, he's no Einstein when it comes to most things.
Snore Level: Get your earplugs ready... 
Affection Level: Extreme. 100% velcro dog who loves to love and be loved.
Descriptors: Friendly. Stubborn. Exuberant. Affectionate. Demanding. High maintenance.
Best features: His perfectly compact meatball physique. His smooshable face and jowls. 
What we love most: He makes you feel like the most important person in the world. He is always up for a snuggle marathon. He prefers to nap with his head in your lap. He smiles.
What makes us laugh: His high-speed paw offering if he thinks there’s a treat to be had.
What he loves most: Tie. His human and the bag of snackies on the table.
What else he loves: Attention. Bully sticks. Adventures. Marrow bones. Car rides. Watching the world go by from the car window. His blue football squeaky toy, which no longer squeaks, for the record. 
Working on: Embracing and enjoying his alone time. Jumping when excited. Begging. Hoovering food and treats.
Gotta be honest: He pulls like an ox (let's not forget he has a low center of gravity, meaty neck, and muscles for days) and sounds like a screaming pterodactyl-gremlin when he sees another dog on leash. #workinprogress #yesitisthatbad
Dogs: Nope. Way too overstimulated when he sees other dogs and his common sense goes out the window. 
Cats: Another no. 
Kids: Yes, but 10+ as he will knock a little one down when he’s excited.
House trained: Yep!
Wanted: Bully-savvy family in search of a co-pilot for daily adventures. Should be attentive and patient and equally dedicated to continued leash training and lengthy cuddle sessions. Appreciation for snoring and love of snacks and sharing the couch are a must.
Wilbur is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative and microchipped. He’s available for adoption to residents of CT and surrounding states. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application from Omdrescue.org.

animal.description:
Meet Walter!! We have no idea what breed he is, maybe Basenji/Rat Terrier? Whatever he is we do know he is simply adorable!!!! Walter is super sweet, super loving, super snuggly, and just an all around great little dog. He hates the crate and tries to get out but settles down eventually. He'd rather be under the bed or in your lap! Walter is learning to go potty outside but still wears a belly band inside to keep the furniture safe. Walter is great around other dogs but we don't know about cats. Because of his personality we're guessing he'd be great with kids but haven't tested this out yet. Walter is approximately 6 years old and weighs approximately 13-15 pounds. Adoption fee is $250 + $15 microchip Walter is being fostered in North Olmsted/Westlake, OH

 

Our adoption fee includes vaccinations, wormer and in all adult dogs, spay/neuter.

 

Where does my adoption fee go? Ask your vet how much he/she charges for the following:

 

Spaying/neutering $150-300

Distemper vaccination $20-30 x2

Rabies vaccination $15-25

Heartworm test $15-35

Flea/tick treatment $50-200

Wormer $20-$45

Dental $100-$300

Microchip $25-$50
Not to mention the office visit cost.

Please consider all that is done for your rescue dog prior to complaining about the adoption fee.

 

Mini Mutts Rescue DOES consider adopting to families with young children. Please send an email if you'd like an application to adopt this dog - nels44077@yahoo.com 

A fenced yard is preferred.

 

 

We do adopt outside the state of Ohio. However, we require the adopting family to drive to Ohio to meet/adopt the dog applying for. Should this be more than a day's drive, we can arrange transport with the adopting family driving at least half way.

 

 

 

.


We use Patented Kuranda Dog Beds because they are durable, chew proof and easy to clean. If you would like to donate a bed to us, click here.

animal.description:
Name: Magda
Breeds: Pit Bull Mix
Age: Young Adult
Gender: Female

Magda is a beautiful, pointy ear pittie mix who despite her sunny disposition has not had a life of rainbows and sunshine. She came into the shelter as a stray with scarring around her neck from a previously embedded collar. Ending up in the shelter was the best thing that happened to her...she was adored there and they worked so hard to find a rescue to take her. It's impossible not to fall in love with her. From her silly wiggles, her smile when she gets a butt scratch, her joy at racing around the yard with her dog pals, and her champion snuggle skills, Magda is a heart stealer. She is excellent with other large breed dogs and loves to play with them. She would love a playful canine companion in her new home though she loves people just as much. Typical to bully breeds, she can be a bit mouthy when she plays but is learning that toys are for mouthing and to contain her happy exuberance. She has a higher prey drive so needs a home without cats, small critters, or small/toy dogs...they look too much like little rabbits and squirrels to resist chasing and getting rough with them. Walks rank high on her favorite things and she is learning her leash manners.  Magda is housetrained (though expect transition accidents like any dog), crates well for the workday, and is learning basic commands. She is extremely eager to learn and loves to hear what a good girl she is. She would be the star of an obedience class for sure!

Requirements: Home with yard space. No cats

animal.description:
Hello, how do you do?

The name is Nathan.  I'm a cute boy, ain't I??  I'm a Blue Lacy mix, and boy do I like to have a job to do!

My story starts off sadly I'm afraid.  A daughter of one of the Lucies volunteers is in the real estate business.  A house was being sold, and the previous home owner made the daughter aware that I was a stray that had been coming up.  They had been feeding me and were worried what would become of me when they moved.  They were so sweet and good to take care of me like that.

So she reached out to Lucies to see if they could help.  They agreed that they could help and would take me to the vet and be boarded and then eventually bring me to the rescue once a spot opened up.

A few days later, I came up to eat and was totally exhausted and in excruciating pain.  Mean, filthy, stinky wild hogs had gotten ahold of me and attacked me!!  I was immediately taken to the vet and underwent surgery to close the large wound on my back, complete with a drainage tube.

Even though I didn't know these Lucies people, I was very patient with them once it was time to remove the tube, and even more so when the stitches were removed.  These are some very special people and I'm very grateful for them!

I'd truly love to be someone's lap dog.  I just love to be held tightly and loved on.  Oh, I do NOT like fireworks.  And one more thing, I truly hate pork now ;)

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

Austin is a senior sweetheart... he needs love and care from a very special person. Austin had a horrible life before we rescued him... in the photo above in his crate shows his scraggly fur and long nails.  

Austin has seen an eye specialist and is blind in one eye... he doesnt seem to care. 
 He had bronchitis when we rescued him, and that is all cleared up.  He also had a horrid flea allergy which left him with no fur on his rump... but his hair is growing in soft and full now.  He must have been outside 24/7.  

We just know there is someone out there who is willing to love him.

From his foster mommy...

I NEED YOU

I need you.  I was left on my own
No inside place to call home.
My fur was matted and frizzy
Some was falling out. I was in a tizzy.

Standing in the middle of Street Miller
I received a blessing and thriller.
Warm friendly hands closed around me
Funny, I thought to myself “now I’m free”
Of cold, poor food and no company.

My trust of two legs is still an issue but
I no longer need to cry into a tissue.
My needs are many
I know now people are friendly.

All I need is patience, guidance and love
And a friendly, understanding two legged angel from above.
Could I be someone you could care for and love?

I need you . . do you need me ?

animal.description:
Looking Glass Animal Rescue is a 501c3 virtual rescue, using a network of dedicated fosters throughout the Northeast to care for our animals until adoption. You may be required to travel if approved for adoption.


ABOUT TROOPER - From his foster...

Hurricane Delta hit our small part of the world in Louisiana October 9, 2020, and devastated much of our area, for a second time, after Hurricane Laura had wreaked havoc on nearby cities. We had our power restored sooner this time, on October 15th, although not all of our area had their electricity back. In that night, around 10:30pm, I received a frantic message from a friend who had a tree fallen in her house. She thought she could hear a puppy crying under her home. She felt terrible and was in tears because she told me she and her daughters had heard something the night before, but they have their own furbabies and thought it was was of them making a sound inside their home. Keep in mind this was 6 days after a second major storm had turned all of our lives into a nightmare that we all hoped to wake up from. I ran upstairs to tel my husband that I was driving to Jennings to get under my friend's house to get the puppy. He told me that I wasn't thinking rationally again (he is the police chief), since there was still a curfew plus not all street lights were on. We wouldn't be able to even see enough with flashlights. My friend and I stayed on the phone for a long time that night. We both cried and prayed. A lot.

My husband assured me that our wonderful ACO Chelsi would go first thing in the morning.

That she did, with a police officer. Chelsi crawled under the home, and Trooper hobbled away in fear, crying all the way, in the direction of the police officer, who scooped him up.

Chelsi took Trooper straight to the vet. It was determined he most likely was hit by a car. He had a fractured pelvis and broken humerus bone in his front right leg.

That was October 16, 2020. Trooper went back to the shelter and Chelsi made a post saying what the estimates costs would be for the surgery to help this precious little boy. Donations poured in to our nonprofit JDAWG, and we raised MORE than we asked. Trooper's surgery was scheduled.

On October 17, I had to say the hardest goodbye ever when my foster Teddy left on his Looking Glass Animal Rescue transport to his new family. A piece of my heart went to New York that morning. (I now am overjoyed with Teddy's beautiful family, and he lives like a king.). We had plans to pick up Trooper on our way back from letting our Teddy go. I cried the whole way to the shelter. Then I saw that sweet face that actually tried to smile at me when I held him. He cried when I picked him up; I soon learned how to hold him so he was in less pain. I held him close and cried with him many, many times when he was hurting(he had medicine for the pain). He whines when he can't find me, but is getting better at me not being around 24/7.

His surgery went well, and a pin was placed to stabilize his bone. He never was crated because he had a hard time moving around, so he is pad trained, and is going outside now, but still has accidents every now and then. He had the pin removed, then was xrayed after being neutered on January 5. His leg is almost 100% healed!!! Our vet said he may have early onset arthritis, but he runs and plays now without the heartbreaking cries of pain that we heard at the beginning with any slight wrong movement. He is just the sweetest boy!! Would truly make a wonderful family companion. So loving and so deserving of the most amazing home!! He is super handsome, too!!

Trooper is UTD on all vaccinations, heartworm negative and takes a monthly preventative. He loves carrot sticks and mostly any food or snack he can get. We feed him 4Health Small bites from Tractor Supply. He is spoiled and very loves attention. He enjoys playing with all our dogs, but runs to me if the playing gets too rough for him. He is a precious soul and we are looking for a very special home for this baby.

I love Trooper so very much and the only rescue I entrust him to is Looking Glass. We have been in communication ever since Teddy left my arms and Trooper came into them.

Looking Glass Animal Rescue is a 501(c)(3) virtual rescue, using a network of dedicated fosters throughout the Northeast to care for our animals until adoption. You may be required to travel if approved for adoption.

Applications can be submitted through https://lgarinc.org/adoption-application/. Please note that you must be 25 years of age to adopt and we reserve the right to refuse adoption to anyone. All applications are subject to review and approval and a tax-deductible adoption donation is required to be paid prior to adoption day.

Please note that you must be 25 years of age to adopt and we reserve the right to refuse adoption to anyone. Please be advised that we will not approve adoptions to persons who mislead or fail to provide accurate information on this application. Incomplete applications will not be processed.

Holly is a beautiful girl who’s sweet personality and nice demeanor charms everyone she meets - she always seems to have a smile on her face and a wagging tail. She does well with other dogs and seems to like the cats at her foster as well. Holly is learning to walk well on leash and while she may be a bit timid trying new things, she is eager to learn. Holly was abandoned and left to wander around. Fortunately for her, she wandered up to a good Samaritan's home and decided to hang around as she was getting fed. They contacted animal control and sadly, nobody was looking for her. So, we are not sure what circumstances she came from, but we are all happy Holly is safe now in rescue. She would do great with a kind family to show her the ropes, a fenced in yard and with dog or cat companions...she's a sweetie :)

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Meet Dirk! Dirk is believed to be around 2 years old, and likely an Olde English Bulldog, or an english/American mix.

Dirk came in as a stray. The family that had found him wanted to keep him, but said he was getting nippy with the kids - not surprising, as he had wicked ear infections and some angry skin issues. He is always going to have some sensitive handling issues, as he has a lot of scar tissue built up in his ears from chronic infection, and we believe may at one point have had a broken tail. And he *hates* baths. So, we are looking for an adult-only home for him. *Possibly* with an easy-going female dog, but bulldogs are known to often develop issues with other dogs. He's done ok so far with limited meets, but absolutely no small dogs as he will run them over. Prospective adopters should have bulldog or similar experience, and be able to financially maintain future medical issues. He is on a limited-ingredient (non-prescription) food. He is NOT a lazy bulldog, and likes to keep active and is very playful.

For more information or to request an adoption application, please stop into the shelter, or contact us via email.

bollmanje@baycounty.net

animal.description:
Muddy as he is called, or sometimes Rex which he is also called, is an active, quick learning, high energy, conks out when tired, plays well with others fun dog.  He is just a year old and would do great with someone who is looking for a four legged companion to take on adventures, participate in doggy obedience and spend a lot of time playing outside followed by a nice nap!
Notes from his foster mom:
12/26/2021
Some things to share about Rex:
-he likes to be outside
-he has tons of energy and it takes a lot right now to tire him although he does slow down and lay still 
-he gets along well with his foster brothers and has learned to titrate himself down a bit when playing with Jax (with Jax’s vocalization) our older dog
 -his body is slight and he is very fast; we would not recommend a non-fenced yard 
-I let him out one afternoon not realizing there was a squirrel on the bird feeder; 
Rex was faster than the squirrel; he cornered it on the ground where two sections of the fence meet and tussled with it until it managed to get away and run up the tree; 
it took a lot of doing to redirect him from jumping up on the tree trunk; a home with small animals may not be a good fit -he is very smart and friendly and learns quickly; he also is sensitive to a stern voice -he does well in the crate and does signal when he needs to go out (sometimes he will ring the bells we have hanging on the door handle) -his relationship with food is complicated; he eats to quickly (I have ordered a slow feeding bowl); he is not food aggressive but does hover very closely over the other two while they are eating; we feed the dogs twice a day and Rex seems to be continuously hungry (nosing at the food bag, pushing the empty bowl on the floor); not sure if he’s still not comfortable here or perhaps he didn’t know where his next meal was coming from in whatever environment he came out of) -Sam and Rex will drink out of the water bowl at the same time -Sam and Jax are good role models for him and he pays attention to both of them

1/7/2021
Rex is doing well with his foster brothers and learning how to take turns.  
Did you know that he is very active? ?  Oh my goodness! 
 He is smart and learns new things pretty quickly including letting me try to wipe some of the mud off his paws before he comes in the house. 
 He lifts his feet for me now.  The slow feeder bowl has helped with his eating. 
 He does have a bad habit of being very persistent with begging/surfing for people food. 
 That correction will take a bit of time.  He loves to be outside and does not seem to be bothered by any element he has come into contact with so far.  Cold, ice, rain, puddles, mud - he takes it all in stride.  Rex and Sam like to play chase.  Rex is faster so he is usually the chasee.  One afternoon Rex ran full blast toward the side of the deck and at the last moment dove under and army crawled the length of the deck underneath exiting the other side covered in mud.  Yikes!  He had a blast and just kept going.

The one attached photo is a rare moment of complete conk out for Rex.

animal.description:
ADOPTED!!  
His name is "Roadie".  He is a 9-10 yr old rough coat Jack Russell. 
Roadie has lived on a farm he is originally from Arkansas.
He lost his home when the family divorced.  He is crate and leash trained, and according to the family, completely house trained.  
Very handsome fella, but VERY overweight.   Needs to be on a program of real food, NOT KIBBLE.  Meat and veggies. 
Has great personality, very sweet and responsive.
Is good with children and good with other dogs and cats.
He has couple of fatty tumors. Seen by vet, determined to be harmless. 
The owner has just gone through divorce recently and a work related injury and is not working and will not be returning. 
Email us and share! almosthomerescue@gmail.com------------------------------------------------------------------------------------TO BE CONSIDERED TO ADOPT A DOG FROM ALMOST HOME RESCUE YOU MUST FIRST COMPLETE THE ADOPTION APPLICATION.  YOU WILL FIND THE ONLINE FORM HERE -
https://almosthomedogrescue.com/adoption_application/
If you have questions please email us at:  AlmostHomeRescue@gmail.com or you can call us at 941-704-4765
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALL DOGS ADOPTED FROM ALMOST HOME RESCUE ARE SPAYED OR NEUTERED, MICROCHIPPED, VACCINES UP TO DATE AND HEARTWORM TESTED.  
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
PLEASE READ!  
1. Jack Russell Terriers need homes with a secure fence.  Underground fencing is NOT safe for a  Jack Russell.  
2. Jack Russell terriers are bred to be hunting dogs and are not suited to apartment or condo life.  The hunting instincts and prey drive cannot be trained out of  these terriers and they will stay active in this way all their lives.
3. We do not adopt Jack Russell Terriers to families withe small children (under 6) as terriers are not patient with the antics of a small toddler.   
4. Jack Russell Terriers can not safely coexist in a home with cats, birds, ferrets, hamsters, rabbits, etc, as terriers were bred to hunt and can kill small animals.  They are hunters and they never give up. 
5. Please keep an open mind and consider your lifestyle both today and 10 years from now before you apply for a dog that may not be a good fit for the long run.

animal.description:
Meet little TInkerbell. This poor old gal lost her human and then got shuffled around family members she didn't know for several months before being dumped at the pound. As a result, Tinkerbell has developed some attitude and will snap/bite if you're not slow and careful with her. Tinkerbell is older and has been neglected as you can see by the missing fur on her rump. With good food and proper care we expect this fur to grow in eventually. Tinkerbell LOVES human food!! She turns her nose up at bacon treats and gobbles a bite of bread. She is housetrained and will go outside and come back inside when finished. She knows her name and will follow you or just go lay down on a doggie bed somewhere. Tinkerbell sticks to herself and will tolerate a good petting of her back but be careful, when she's done putting up with it she will growl then snap so watch/listen carefully. Of course, all this could change as she realizes she's safe and loved from here on out but we make no guarantee of this. Tinkerbell just needs a loving home who understands she's just a cranky old dog. A home who will love her no matter what, feed her, give her several dog beds to choose from, has a yard for her to wander a bit and do her business, and let her live out her retirement years in peace. Is this you? Approximate Age: 13 years old Approximate Weight: 13 pounds Adoption Fee: TBD Tinkerbell is being fostered in North Olmsted/Westlake, OH

 

Our adoption fee includes vaccinations, wormer and in all adult dogs, spay/neuter.

 

Where does my adoption fee go? Ask your vet how much he/she charges for the following:

 

Spaying/neutering $150-300

Distemper vaccination $20-30 x2

Rabies vaccination $15-25

Heartworm test $15-35

Flea/tick treatment $50-200

Wormer $20-$45

Dental $100-$300

Microchip $25-$50
Not to mention the office visit cost.

Please consider all that is done for your rescue dog prior to complaining about the adoption fee.

 

Mini Mutts Rescue DOES consider adopting to families with young children. Please send an email if you'd like an application to adopt this dog - nels44077@yahoo.com 

A fenced yard is preferred.

 

 

We do adopt outside the state of Ohio. However, we require the adopting family to drive to Ohio to meet/adopt the dog applying for. Should this be more than a day's drive, we can arrange transport with the adopting family driving at least half way.

 

 

 

.


We use Patented Kuranda Dog Beds because they are durable, chew proof and easy to clean. If you would like to donate a bed to us, click here.

he is smart and learns quickly and can be adept at training the humans caring for him.  For example, he knows to sit in front of the refrigerator just at bedtim and wait for his bedtime treat of a hot dog treat.  Smart boy.

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Emery.  Did you know that the name Emery is a dark granular rock used to make abrasive powder?  I didn't either until just now ;)  I however, am not abrasive at all.  I love to mix and mingle and play!

So me and a sweet dog friend of mine were found hanging out on this lady's porch. She called up the peeps at Lucies Project to see if they could take us. They had asked her if she had any safe place to put us until they could come and get us. Unfortunately, she did not. No fence or anything. So, they then asked her to take us to the vet for safekeeping, since Lucies was full at that time.

The technician at the vet said that he lived on the county road that we were found on and he would see if he could find our owners. Surely we belonged to someone! The only thing he could find out was that the people in the area were tired of us chasing their cattle.....oops. We were just having a little fun after all ;)

Our days were numbered, so we sure were glad when Lucies found a space for us :)

I'm very outgoing and I respectfully sit when I want some attention. How about considering me for adoption? I'd love to have a furever home, with a fence of course so I can't wander around :)

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.
 
Please complete and return the adoption application to meet any of our adoptable dogs.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Pit Mix|4 yrs|45 lbs|$400.00Sophie is a 2-year-old, 40-pound pitbull-mix in search of a home that fits just right.

Sophie finds that there is no such thing as too long of a walk. She loves to wind through the neighborhood route, and wants to play with any other dog she meets, big or small. Whether too cold outside, too hot outside or just right she is sure to ensure that her family gets out everyday for some time in the fresh air. This girl is happy to be where her people are, whether as co-captain of the car, or enjoying a toy by the fireplace. Her favorite indoor hobbies include finding that just right pressure of the stuffed toy where the stuffing meets the squeaker. She will chew and chew until the squeaker is no longer. At the end of a playful and exciting day I will snuggle up right next to my people ready for a good Netflix binge or deep read.

Sophie has gotten along well with mama cat, which she is curious about, but ignores; or papa dog, which she is always trying to goad into playing with her. She enjoys the energy of a baby or young human, but in her playful exuberance may jump up and knock a young tot down, so a home with a young child may not be the best fit. Sophie would also be happy to be the only furry darling in her home.

Sophie is still very much a puppy, and will need to continue her leash training in her forever home. She has excellent manners, making her an impeccable houseguest, and will take treats gently from her human.

Sophie, like Golidlocks, is in search of a place to dine, play, and rest that is just right. This loving girl is looking for a home with long walks, short bursts of play, and cuddles mixed in throughout the day. Start the first chapter of Sophie's fairytale by filling out an application to meet her at https://rescuecrew.org/adopt-animal-in-need/#adoptionapplication

The adoption fee covers the cost of the animal's spay/neuter surgery, microchipping, FIV/FeLK testing (for cats) or Heartworm Testing (for dogs), deworming and all core age appropriate vaccinations. For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well. Thank you.

animal.description:
Meet Adoptable PENNY! Looking for the perfect proportions of sweet, sassy, and smart?  Do you find yourself missing that one special ingredient? If so, Penny will add the perfect amount of spice to your life! Penny is a somewhat dominant female with a medium to high energy level, weighs approximately 50 lbs., and is approximately 2 years old.  She is a wonderful, playful little girl who is very dedicated to her people and is happiest being by your side.

Penny co-exists with balanced, male and female dogs in her household, but could potentially do well as the only canine in the household.  Due to natural prey drive, Penny cannot coexist with small animals.  She needs consistent, loving leadership, as Penny will happily take lead without it.  We advise any children in the household are 10 years and older.

Penny will be confirmed heartworm negative in February, is current on vaccinations and heartworm/flea preventative, spayed, crate-trained, housebroken, microchipped, and knows basic commands. Penny is currently on Proin Chewable Tablets 2 times a day for some bladder issues that arose after administration of steroids. Proin helps regain proper muscle tone for bladder control and works 100%! Penny will be weaned down in hopes she will no longer need it. Many dogs are very success at being weaned off. We like to be truthful about our dogs so adopters know the needs of our adoptable dogs so please do not let this minor issue sway you away from considering this wonderful girl that will be a wonderful companion!

If you are interested in adopting Penny, please email streethearts.animal.rescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: Pearl
*Age: 3 years
*Current Weight: 50 pounds
*Rescued from: Texas
*Adoption fee: $375 (plus $125 spay/neuter deposit, which is refundable when spay/neuter agreement is fulfilled)
*Health: up to date on required vaccines

Howdy, I'm Pearl.  Hmm, what can I say about me?  The first photo my foster mom saw of me I was skin and bones.  Luckily, a lady nearby started feeding me, she could tell I had puppies stashed away somewhere.  Eventually, I trusted this lady and brought my two puppies to her.  I was right to trust her, she helped find homes for my puppies, one of them traveled to a SNARR adaptor in the NE last year and a SNARR foster mom for me.  Before I could travel, my foster mom was concerned my Heartworm disease was pretty advanced so I stayed with her to complete my Heartworm treatment.  My last injection was at the end of December, so now it's my turn to find an awesome forever home.  I'd love a yard, I'm a country girl so a big yard would be awesome.  My foster mom would like it fenced so I stay safe.  I love a soft place to lay and often can find me in the big dog bed in the living room or on one of the recliners.  I'm a sucker for affection.  Sometimes, I get too excited and a bit mouthy because I love to be loved so smaller kids might not be the best for me.  I love antlers, peanut butter, and generally enjoy most chew toys.  I've enjoyed my canine foster siblings but sometimes I can a little grumpy with my sisters.  I'm crate and house trained and good on a leash.  Well, I guess that's it in a nutshell.  If you are looking for a confident, affectionate walking buddy that love to be spoiled maybe I'm the girl for you.

Pearl was rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. She will be arriving at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY on Feb 15th ready for adoption! To apply to adopt Pearl, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

IMPORTANT: This dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a strictly-enforced signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Howdy,

My name is Elijah.  It's cool to have a biblical name, don't ya think?  After all, Elijah was a prophet and a miracle worker!  Of course, God hasn't performed any miracles through me like raining fire down from heaven, but there's always tomorrow!

So me and a sweet dog friend of mine were found hanging out on this lady's porch.  She called up the peeps at Lucies Project to see if they could take us.  They had asked her if she had any safe place to put us until they could come and get us.  Unfortunately, she did not. No fence or anything.  So, they then asked her to take us to the vet for safekeeping, since Lucies was full at that time.

The technician at the vet said that he lived on the county road that we were found on and he would see if he could find our owners.  Surely we belonged to someone!  The only thing he could find out was that the people in the area were tired of us chasing their cattle.....oops.  We were just having a little fun after all ;)

Our days were numbered, so we sure were glad when Lucies found a space for us :)

I'm a sweet boy and I have the cutest pointy ears, don't you think?  How about considering me for adoption?  I'd love to have a furever home, with a fence of course so I can't wander around :)  

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Charley was given up to the Bedford Humane Society at three months old, because the lady and her 12 year old daughter could no longer care for her.  They took her in at three weeks and the constant care was more than they could handle.  She did not know the breed of the Mom and was told the pup was a male so she named her Charley.  She does answer to her name.  So it is only a guess as to her breed and only going by her looks.  Charley is a very active girl and wants a lot of attention.  She is responsive to training and loves to play fetch with her toys.  She is learning not to jump up on everything.  She needs a family that will have patience with her training and give her the attention she craves.  She is crate trained but not completely housebroken.  She is learning to walk well on the leash without jumping all over.  Charley would probably do better with an older child in the family that will be consistent with her training.  She is tentative meeting other dogs but would probably be ok with another dog when she feels comfortable.  At three months she has not had a lot of socializing.  Another dog might be good for her to help keep her active in play.  Charley has been dewormed, microchipped, and has been started on heartworm  preventive and has received the Distemper-Parvo combination vaccine, and Kennel Cough vaccine. 

 Since she is not yet spayed, Charley is not available for adoption outside of the counties contiguous to Bedford County.

For more information, please call the Bedford Humane Society at 540-586-6100, or go to www.bhsva.org/adoptions-home.htm to fill out an adoption application.

First step in applying - visit our website and download our application which can be found at www.crossourpawsrescue.com

Submit your application to crossourpaws@gmail.com once complete. Include photos and videos (required due to covid as we will not enter your home to complete the home-check).

READ ENTIRE POST! Please only apply if you meet the following requirements;

- Experience working with large-breed dogs specifically German Shepherds
- Experience with force-free training and counter-conditioning
- A home with a secure yard with at least a 5 ft wood fence (no chain-link)
- You are located within the GVRD (Greater Vancouver)
- You are an adult-only home with no kids or cats (we are unsure about felines)
- You have the time and patience to work, train and raise a German Shepherd Dog
- You feed a high quality diet and believe strongly in holistic care/therapies 
- Have the funds for vet care and pet insurance

More about Regal Rocky...

Rocky is 2 years old, neutered and weighs about 85 lbs. He is learning some long-overdue leash manners as he's never been trained. Sadly, Rocky was kept in a cage on a blueberry farm so he's a little behind in his training. Rocky loves other dogs but can be reactive on leash depending on the other dog/s (work in progress). He loves the dogs in his foster home and plays nicely. Rocky will need a strong handler and has not been trained to recall as of yet (no off-leash). He was neutered in early Jan and has fully recovered. House-training has been going great and no accidents since the first day he arrived. We do believe Rocky was mis-handled in the past as he can be hand-shy around his head/collar so patience there is needed. He has some drive but not over the top like some German Shepherds. He loves his toys and is learning to trade. Once settled, Rocky loves to climb onto the sofa and cuddle in for a good movie or show. LOTS of potential in this HANDSOME boy!!!

animal.description:
Fred is looking for a very special owner, and we're confident the right person is out there for him.  Could that be you?

The big wide world worries Fred, and some aspects of it out-right scare him, so he's looking for a life where he's not expected to go out and about, nor constantly meet new people in his home.  He has done fine meeting other dogs, but he does not want to live with another dog -- he gets very possessive of what he considers valuable, including his person.

When Fred is feeling safe and comfortable, he's very playful, and loves to play in our fenced yards, in all weather.  He likes walks (and hikes in his previous home), but only in places where he's not exposed to other people.  He will also need to stay on-leash -- if he's scared by a person, or loud noises, he wants to run away.

Fred needs a human who is committed to never putting a shock collar on him; someone who understands that training with pain and fear doesn't work, but can actually cause long-term harm. Fred is very smart, and has done really well with Positive Reinforcement training, and has good obedience skills. 

If you can provide Fred an active life, where he can devote himself completely to you, where he feels safe and loved, without other dogs, cats, or kids, please call our Adoption Center at 802-476-3811 to schedule a time to talk with an adoption counselor to determine if you should meet him.  It's possible it will take more than one meeting for Fred to feel ready to go home with you.

animal.description:
Luna is a  2 year old, 48 lb. female
The best guess at her breed is: Mixed Breed
She would be good in a home with: Kids 10+
She prefers a home without: Dogs, Cats

Luna is a medium energy, extremely affectionate girl. Her favorite activity is when volunteers visit her in her room for cuddles and to play tug of war. She love to be close to her people and has an endless supply of kisses. She is extremely affectionate!

When Luna spends time outside, she likes to play with you and will do a few zoomies around the yard. Luna would like an active forever home who will exercise her by taking her on walks or playing in the backyard. She thrives on human attention and would like a family who isn't gone for too long.

Luna has successfully played with a 60 lb. male shepherd at our shelter but since then hasn't been able to make another canine friend. She would like to be the only dog and will need a family who understands she doesn't like other dogs. This doesn't seem to affect her when she is on walks in the park. She passes by dogs at a distance and doesn't bark at them.

Volunteers enjoy walking Luna and report back that she rides well in the car and walks well on a leash.

Luna knows how to sit and is very food motivated. She appears to be house trained as she doesn't have accidents in her crate or in her room when left loose.

--

Our hours: In an effort to limit the number of visitors at our shelter during this time, visitors are limited to approved applicants only.


Instructions on how to fill out our online application are on our website here: https://www.lighthouseanimalshelter.org/application-instructions

We are receiving a high number of applications at this time. Please be patient with us while we adjust to these new changes and keep in mind that our volunteers process the applications as quickly as their schedules allow.

We do not adopt on a first-come-first-serve basis, but rather by the best match between dog and family, although we will factor in the order of applications if there are equally good matches.

How you can help us process your application:
Please call all of your references (landlord, if applicable, vet(s) and personal references) before filling out an application to let them know that we will be calling. We are an all-volunteer program and volunteers often make reference calls from their cell phone. It will be a number your personal reference does not recognize. We understand most people will screen their calls from unknown numbers so please tell them to keep an eye on their voicemail and give the volunteer a call back at their earliest convenience. We may end up playing phone tag with your personal references but will reach out to you if we need further assistance in reaching them.

How we process your application:
Once we receive your application, we will check home ownership or landlord permission, personal references and vet references. We will reach out to you if we have questions during the process or if we are having trouble reaching your references either through email or phone. We will contact you when your application is fully processed to discuss how you would like to proceed with your application and to discuss dogs in our care who will be a good match for you and anyone involved in the adoption.

Our adoption fee:
Our adoption fee is $400 ($415 if paid by PayPal) which covers the costs of vetting (spay, vaccinations, heartworm testing, preventatives while in our care, deworming and microchip) and any boarding or transport fees incurred in each dog's rescue.

Believing she's a lap dog, she also loves snuggling with her foster mom on her couch and sleeping right up against her in bed at night. Fond of toys, ropes and bones, she's slowly learning to enjoy being outdoors, seldom barks and is motivated by food and treats, accepting all of them gently. She understands "no" but knows no other commands, is almost fully housetrained, is learning to be less possessive of her foster mom and needs to work on her leash skills. With much still to learn and so much to give, Russia will thrive in a patient and loving home committed to completing her training and educating her fully in return for her own enduring loyalty and love.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description: Hi ... Gucci here! Yep I'm a little guy, so I was given a BIG name like the designer ... GUCCI. I'm a tiny poodle mix with a face so cute you just want to smooch it! animal.description:
Hi! Let me introduce myself. My name is Alberto...I'm a terrier/schnauzer mix and weigh 21lbs. Camo rescued me from the shelter and I'm so thankful!!! I'm vaccinated, neutered and microchipped. I am HW positive, so I will have to go through treatment but don't worry - Camo covers all the cost. I'm good with other dogs..I will chase and bark at cats, but would never hurt them.  I would do good with in any home expect probably not little kiddos, since I'm a "special guy". See..I have this little head tilt that the vet couldn't figure out and sometimes I will bark at the air but it's only when I get super nervous. I would love a yard to run and and explore. I'm not great in a crate, but prefer a xpen. I'm potty trained, but need to be taken out every 2-3 hours. I'm leash trained and like to go on "strolls" around the neighborhood, but due to my anxiety please don't take me to a dog park.  I love to carry stuff animals around and take them outside with me or just snuggle with them. I'm a happy guy looking for the perfect furever family that appreciates my personality.  I hope to meet you soon!!!

You can also read more about me here: www.thepupblog.com/post/meet-alberto

Alberto's adoption fee is $300 plus 8.25% sales tax. 

ALL adoptions require a completed application, vet check, home check and final contract.  The application to adopt can be found at www.camorescue.com.

Adoption fees are variable. Up to date vaccines, microchip, spay/neuter are included in the fee.

Once your application has been approved, we will put you in touch with the foster to set up a  meet and greet. We are a foster based RESCUE, not a shelter. All of our dogs are in individual foster homes. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We select the best applicant for each dog, based on the dog's needs. 
For the safety of our small breed dogs and based on our past experiences, we will not place our dogs in homes with large breed dogs.    

CAMO rescue is a 501c3 whose primary focus is rescuing small dogs from the euthanasia list from high kill TX shelters.   
EIN # is 46-5486022
We rescue 800+ animals a year.

Follow us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/camorescue

Our donation link is http://www.paypalme/camorescue 

We are strictly volunteer based, no salaries are paid and 100% of donations go towards rescuing dogs.

animal.description:
MEET RINGO!

This gorgeous, sweet and shy senior came to us when his person passed away. Ringo has adjusted very nicely with us, but we feel it's time for him to find his final forever home. Ringo is a 12 year old, 68 lb, Carolina Dog AKA an American Dingo. That's right! Ringo is a Dingo, and whether that was done on purpose or not, we think it suits him just fine.

Ringo lived with another dog his age who has since been adopted. He takes a while to warm up to a new person, but once he decides you're okay, he will reward you with letting you rub his oh-so-soft fur.

Ringo knows 'sit' and is working on 'down.' He has no leash manners, but we know once he settles into his new routine with his person, he will learn quickly. Like a true southern gentleman, Ringo prefers ambling in the yard as opposed to zoomying. He will bark in support of his zoomying friends, but Ringo is very much a spectator.

Ringo is scheduled to be neutered on January 28th, but we wanted to list him now because we would love for him to recover from his surgery in his new home.

Ringo has done well with dogs and has interacted favorably to cats and chickens. We think children would cause him to cower, so an adult home would be ideal.

He is up-to-date, but still needs to be neutered. His adoption fee is $250.
