animal.description:
Hi everyone my name is Doja! I am a large breed boy with a large heart that matches my size. I absolutely love affection from my humans. Belly rubs? HECK YES! I came to CCRC in bad shape with a bullet inside my arm from being shot. They got me the care I needed and now I'm ready to find my forever home! I would love a home without other animals or a calm dog that doesn't want to play. I am a chill dog BUT I LOVE GOING FOR WALKS! I'm an older dude with a young heart! I enjoy showing off what a smart boy I am by showing all the cute tricks I know (for treats of course). Please come meet me - fill out an application and someone will be in touch ASAP.

We do not have a facility for you to visit.

WE PROCESS APPLICANTS AND SET APPOINTMENTS BASED ON THE ORDER APPLICATIONS ARE RECEIVED

, so while you are welcome to email
ccrcdogs@ccrcdogs.com
with specific questions, you will want to complete the

ONLINE APPLICATION

ASAP

,

which can be found at www.ccrcdogs.com,

to secure your position in line for one of our dogs. You can also find

a description of our process on that same page. Puppies will not be available to be seen until their 10 day quarantine has passed. Our adoption fee is $200 for adults and $275 for puppies, which covers the cost of the spay/neuter, age appropriate shots and tests, medications to bring the dog to full health, and a free visit with one of our approved vets after adoption. The majority of dogs at CCRC are obtained from animal control centers, so there is often very little known about their history or even current habits. You can always expect to do some training, regardless of whether you adopt a dog or a puppy, including crate training, house training, and basic manners. CCRC provides a variety of materials and resources to assist you with this, as well as telephone support.

Her name is BELLA.  Owner went from assisted living to hospital, now the dog MUST FIND A NEW HOME.  Ormond Beach, Fl area. Her name is BELLA, she is very sweet, loves to go on walks, friendly to all, but has always been an only dog, thus she needs to stay an only dog. Doesn't like other dogs to approach. She is spayed, up-to-date on all back scenes, and in great health. She could lose a couple pounds! Someone who would put her on the right diet of grain-free food and a few vegetables each day would be doing her a great favor. Right now she is active and very much a happy girl. Please contact us if you can foster her or if you would like to adopt her.
Email - almosthomerescue@gmail com
Cell - 941.704.4765------------------------------------------------------------------------------------TO BE CONSIDERED TO ADOPT A DOG FROM ALMOST HOME RESCUE YOU MUST FIRST COMPLETE THE ADOPTION APPLICATION.  YOU WILL FIND THE ONLINE FORM HERE -
https://almosthomedogrescue.com/adoption_application/
If you have questions please email us at:  AlmostHomeRescue@gmail.com or you can call us at 941-704-4765
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALL DOGS ADOPTED FROM ALMOST HOME RESCUE ARE SPAYED OR NEUTERED, MICROCHIPPED, VACCINES UP TO DATE AND HEARTWORM TESTED.  
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
PLEASE READ!  
1. Jack Russell Terriers need homes with a secure fence.  Underground fencing is NOT safe for a  Jack Russell.  
2. Jack Russell terriers are bred to be hunting dogs and are not suited to apartment or condo life.  The hunting instincts and prey drive cannot be trained out of  these terriers and they will stay active in this way all their lives.
3. We do not adopt Jack Russell Terriers to families withe small children (under 6) as terriers are not patient with the antics of a small toddler.   
4. Jack Russell Terriers can not safely coexist in a home with cats, birds, ferrets, hamsters, rabbits, etc, as terriers were bred to hunt and can kill small animals.  They are hunters and they never give up. 
5. Please keep an open mind and consider your lifestyle both today and 10 years from now before you apply for a dog that may not be a good fit for the long run.

animal.description:
This precious 4 year old Dachshund/border collie spent 1 ½ years in a local shelter.  He was taken in initially due to a cruelty investigation after being rescued from a hoarding situation.  Sadly, until this time he hadn’t had any socialization with humans and was considered semi-feral.

He was terrified of everyone and everything but the shelter staff could see he had potential.  After months of working with him and building his trust, he was making great strides.  Eventually, he became accustomed to his new routine at the shelter, enjoyed being petted and to expect his daily meals.

We learned about this boy and how far the shelter had come with him and decided collectively, that a foster home would be where he would continue to thrive until he was ready for his forever home.

Our wonderful fosters, together with their special dog, have been working with Ducky for about a month now.   He has reached a point where we’re ready to put him up for adoption with some very specific requirements.

Ducky’s new adoptive family will need to be prepared to continue to work with him to overcome his fears and mistrust.  He is wonderful with humans once he gets to know them but is terrified of certain dogs.  

He will absolutely require a home with a docile, patient dog who is willing to continue to show him the ropes.  An intuitive dog, who can read Ducky well and know when to back off and give him his space.  He will also require a child-free, quiet home in the suburbs where there isn’t too much commotion as he continues to gain his confidence and become the best dog he can be.

animal.description:
Cremy is around 10 months old, weighs 50 lbs and was rescued from Puerto Rico. He should grow up to be a medium Sato, known for being extraordinarily loyal and loving dogs.

His foster mom reports: 

Cremy is doing well.  He is playing in the snow and with the other dogs and toys.  I think a quiet house would be best for him.  He does have food aggression but not when being fed it’s with treats (he won’t eat them right away sometimes and will growl/snap at other dogs who try to get near it.  I have been able to take it away from him with no issues). He is also mouthy when playing but is getting better.

The only issue he has is he will bark/growl at strangers who come into the house then he will come and sit by me when they are here.  I’m trying to work on that but between snow storm and COVID we have not had a lot of visitors.  Let anyone know he needs time to adjust to new people.  He would love someone who will snuggle on the bed or couch with him.

I haven’t had the chance to introduce them to kids.  But in my opinion Cremy would be a better fit for kids than Blanky. They have started crate training. 
They get along well with other dogs, we have 3 little ones and they are super sweet and gentle with them.  No cats at home, but sometimes when they see a cat on the street when we are walking they bark like crazy. I think they are good with both men and women.

If you wish to meet them or find out more about them that is not included in their profile, please fill out our adoption application at http://bit.ly/PSDAdopt and our adoption counselor will contact you as soon as possible.

If they are listed on PetFinder, they have not yet been adopted. We take them off PetFinder when we have received enough applications, but that does not mean they have been adopted. 

We do not know who the parents were nor what size they were, so we cannot tell you what breed they are nor what size they will eventually achieve.

animal.description:
Eco is a 4-5 yo possible Golden Retriever/Australian Shepard mix.  He is house and crate trained. He would prefer a suburban life, without all the hustle, bustle, and noise of the big city. He was rescued from Puerto Rico, so he is a medium sized Sato, known for being extraordinarily loyal and loving dogs.
He is currently a little bit overweight and in the process of transitioning to a new food to shed some of those extra pounds. He is good with men and woman.  He is very calm in the home and just lounges around, but is more than happy to romp around the yard with dog friends. 
Eco would do best living in a home without other dogs because he has shown resource guarding with his food ( only with dogs, not people ). Eco is good with other dogs in neutral settings (park, yard, playdates, etc.) and really enjoys playing with other dogs! He is totally fine socializing with other dogs out in the yard, on the leash, and does not guard his toys.  He can have furry friends come over as long as you make sure there is no food out.  
Right now we are recommending a house with no kids for Eco as he has some chronic joint pain (arthritis) that can make him sensitive to the sudden or unpredictable movements small children often make. 
We are looking for a dog experienced adopter who understands Eco and his needs, who will continue to help him shed his extra pounds (drop that pandemic weight!) and never let him be over weight again as it’s crucial for him to stay thin with his arthritis and minor hip dysplasia. 

If you wish to meet them or find out more about them that is not included in their profile, please fill out our adoption application at http://bit.ly/PSDAdopt and our adoption counselor will contact you as soon as possible.

If they are listed on PetFinder, they have not yet been adopted. We take them off PetFinder when we have received enough applications, but that does not mean they have been adopted.

animal.description:
Meet Emmy!

Well hello, my name is Emmy. I'm 6 years old and a very large 104 pounds. My owner passed away and I ended up in the shelter, and then I got saved and got to come to my goster mom's house. Now, after a while of going for walks and having swimming sessions, to get me some much needed excersize, I still wasn't losing weight. So, off to the vet we went for some tests. Come to find out, my thyroid wasnt working the right way, and now I'm on some medicine that will help that, and is pretty affordable. This means I can start losing weight now, and find a forever family to help me on this journey to a healthier me! I'm completely potty trained, so we could go for walks during potty time. At first they might be short walks, but soon I hope they can get longer. I'm good with dogs close to my size, medium to large dogs, but please make sure I don't have to share my food space, I like to eat in peace. I also like older children, the little ones are a bit too loud and active for me. I show interest in cats, although I'm not motivated enough to chase them, I'm unsure if I should live with them or not. I love humans and my foster mom says I'm a very sweet girl. I really enjoy getting affections from my family. I hope I can find a forever family soon, who will help me on this big journey I have ahead of me. They say slow and steady wins the race, and I'm ready to come in first place! Will you be next to me as I lose weight crossing the finish line?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

*TO APPLY GO TO www.LuckyDogRefuge.com*

Meet Tater Tot! This 1 year old, smaller pit mix is as sweet and mellow as they come. Very gentle and a bit shy at first, he's a laid back, chill dude who just wants to hang out with his people and take life pretty easy. He puts the good in good boy.

He was found with a wound on his leg (visible in one of the photos) which has since been mended and is healing beautifully. He is being treated for heartworm (covered by the rescue) and will fully recover from that as well. 

Over all, he is a great dog who deserves the best home. Apply now to adopt this sweet potato!

www.LuckyDogRefuge.com 


READ THE FOLLOWING FOR INSTRUCTIONS ON SUBMITTING AN APPLICATION FOR THIS PET:

- The first step towards adoption is to complete an adoption application, which can be found online at our website www.LuckyDogRefuge.com, under the “Apply Now” tab 

or 

at https://forms.gle/LXKMKSnagxLSad668.

- Do NOT use the Petfinder links or email to ask us about our adoptable dog listings - we do not always receive these messages and will not respond to them.

- Please do not ask if a dog is still available - we do our best to update their status as quickly as possible. If a dog is listed for adoption, it means we have not yet approved an adopter and are still accepting applications.

- PLEASE NOTE THAT ONLY APPROVED ADOPTERS WILL BE PERMITTED TO MEET OUR RESCUES.

Thanks for considering a rescue pup!

Adoption fee is $132.50 which includes taxes, DHPL & KC vaccinations, rabies vaccination, heartworm check, monthly heartworm prevention (until they leave), spay/neuter, and microchip. Application process is still required to adopt a sponsored animal. THERE ARE NO PULL FEE'S FOR APPROVED RESCUE’S!

Keep up with us, our events, our adoptable animals, etc on our Facebook page under Hopkins County Humane Society! You can also view our adoptable pets on petfinder.com under Hopkins County Humane Society! Follow us on Instagram and Twitter: @hchs_adopt

Our Adoption Facility is located at 2210 Laffoon Trail Madisonville, KY 42431. We will open the shelter for the public to view our adoptable animals. However, there are strict guidelines we ask everyone to adhere to in order to open back up safely and successfully. Please see the guidelines listed below.

• To view our adoptable animals, visitors must park in the
parking lot and call our office to let us know of your arrival.
• Visitors must remain in their vehicle until an employee can
escort you to one of our three visitor areas.
• No visitors shall be allowed inside the facility for any reason.
We will utilize our outside spaces only, for the safety of our
visitors and staff.
• We will allow one family per visitor area at a time.
• All other visitors must remain in their vehicle until an area is
available.
• Visiting hours will be limited (as listed below), with a priority
to scheduled appointments.
• Paper applications will be permitted.

Our visiting hours will be Monday-Saturday 1:00 p.m. – 3:00 p.m.

Our employees will wear a face covering for your entire visit. We encourage our visitors to also wear a face covering for your safety as well as our staff’s safety.

You may continue to view our adoptable animals on petango.com and submit your application through the same site!

Please note that all intakes will remain by appointment only and curbside only.meet n greets with an approved application. Visit petango.com to fill out application.Please call us 270-821-8965 or privately message us with questions!

animal.description: Named after Forest Gump's Platoon leader from the movie Forest Gump (he lost both of his legs in the war).    We pulled Lieutenant Dan from a high kill shelter in Georgia where his owners dumped him because he was born without front legs.  Dan has no idea that he is handicapped.  He knows how to walk on his rear two legs and he also has wheels to help him get around.  He has life all figured out and doesn't let anything get him down.  Dan is super affectionate and eager to please.   He has a wonderful disposition and is described by all as a very special dog.  We think Dan  has the personality and temperament to be a service dog or an emotional support animal .   We know that with the right owner and the opportunity Dan is going to find his purpose.  If you would like to adopt Dan please contact Peggy Stern at pmpstern@yahoo.com.

If she has access to a yard, it must be securely fenced because she can jump a 4 foot fence.

animal.description:
Ginger and Benji are having it ruff. Their owner is very sick and she has made the tough decision to rehome them now so she has peace of mind that they are safe.  We would like them adopted together. They have already lost their loved one (a family member is now caring for them while we look for a home) and we don't want them to lose each other.

Both dogs are spayed/neutered and up to date on shots (last vet visit was June 2020).

Ginger is a Chihuahua mix and weighs about 9 pounds. She is 10 years old. if you are gone for an extended time and leave a puppy pad out for her, she knows to use it.  She likes sitting by her human.

Benji is a Maltese mix and weighs about 18 pounds. He's 12 years old. He is also house trained but needs a puppy pad left out just in case if you're gone an extended period of time.

This sweet pair needs a family who can give them love, care and be there for them in their golden years. The family said they mind well and would like do fine in a family with children or a single person or couple. 

There is a $100 rehoming fee for the pair.  If they are not microchipped, we will have that done prior to going to their new home.

Sadly, Duke’s former mom is very ill now and can no longer care for him, so he is back with us and looking for his next big adventure! He is a great, fun little pooch who needs a dog-savvy owner capable of setting boundaries for him and giving him much-needed exercise, as he loves to take walks! And, psssssst …Duke is a lady’s man so prefers humans of the female persuasion! Duke has some special medical needs that can be easily managed in his next home. He must be the only pet and, sorry, no children. For more information about this sweet, white fluff ball, contact me, Stacey, at stacey.doan@poainc.org. animal.description:
Hi there world, I'm Titan. I'm a black male pitbull pup and I'm about 18 weeks old or so. And I am currently looking for my furever home! I am a little ball of energy, so far weighing in at about 25 lbs or so. My foster mom thinks I will get pretty big but I don't remember much about my real mom and dad so we really can't say. Mommy just judges by my feet, or something like that she said. How weird huh? Anyway though, back to me. I love outside time and playing, and I love my foster siblings! I get along great with my dog brother and sister and I like picking on my kitty sisters, but mommy teaches me that I can't be too rough with them, so I know I have to be sweet in the end. I also love my human little brother. He's still really young so mom doesn't let me play with him too too much but I love every second of it when I do get to! I also love my foster mom and dad! Dad is the best though, since I never get in any kinda trouble with him! Lol. I love mommy too of course, but she tells me when I'm being bad so dad is secretly my favorite! Just don't tell mom! I am crate trained and working on house training. I am getting better with house trainng but I'm still learning, especially being able to hold it in the crate at night. I also love nap time and cuddling on the couch with my humans. It's the best. But like I said before, outside is where I'm most happy and spunky! Overall I am a great pup and I just need someone who will love me and teach me things. Oh yeah, and I need someone who will be okay with me having a small medical issue. I have something that they call ""demodectic mange"". Don't worry, it's not your typical contagious mange that's scary and makes all my hair fall out. My foster mom says this is something that I was born with that was passed to me either through my mom or dad, so it's nothing I can help or change. But mom says it's easily controlled/managed with a liquid medicine that I take by mouth just once daily, and it's not too expensive, so don't stress over that! (Oh, and where you see my hair missing on my leg in my pictures, it's not from the mange. I recently had a small stay at the vet's office and I had to have an IV put in, so they had to shave my hair! But no worries. It will grow back in no time and I'll be as cute as ever!) If you will help me get all the care and love that I need and deserve, I promise to return the favor with furever love, cuddles, licks, naps, walks, and so much more! Please adopt me today!

If you are interested in giving Titan a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us and we will be glad to help!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Li'l Abby (TX) is a female mixed breed puppy rescued in Texas. animal.description:
Matilda is a sweet medium sized dog, who we trapped, after she was dumped with her puppies at Harris Brake Lake. 
Her foster has been working with her ever since & she is quickly coming around! She is great with other 
dogs and excellent with cats (no opportunity to test with children). She is initially shy but once comfortable is an excellent couch companion and very outgoing. She is still working on leash manners but is very house trained and has shown no signs of food aggression. 

Her foster says she needs to drive her around in the car a bit to get her a little more comfortable with that, but she is becoming more & more comfortable on a leash. She would do well with another dog as a companion. It's still a bit difficult to get her really interested in forward motion if there isn't a second dog to interact with. Her foster also reports her greetings are hilarious! She shows her teeth and closes her mouth loudly (I'd not call it a 'snap' though). And her tail tries to greet you at the same time her tongue does. So cute & funny!

Matilda is up to date on all her shots & has been spayed & microchipped.

For more information, please contact Susan at daiseymaggie@yahoo.com.

To make the best possible match for you and the pet, please click below to complete the Adoption Application. 

Once your application has been processed, we'll be in contact. 

We cannot schedule a meet and greet without a completed application. 

If you are viewing this page through PetFinder, Adopt-a-Pet, etc., please go to http://ootwrescue.org/adoption.html to fill out an application or review our Adoption Process.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Jake and I'm around 7 or 8 years old. Before I met my foster parents, I lived outside my whole life which led to me being heartworm positive. Luckily, I have successfully completed my treatment and I am ready for my fur-ever home.

I would be the best fit with someone looking for a companion as I love being right by my human's side. I like other dogs, but I'm happiest when the attention is all on me and I don't have to share my toys or treats. (Absolutely no cats for me.) I'm an easy walker and I do well in public and love to go wherever my human goes.

I am okay around children, but it would be best if you didn't have any younger kids. I can be protective of them and I do not like when they are picked up.

I am mostly calm throughout the day; my foster parents work from home and I love keeping watch over them to make sure they are getting their work done. When I'm not busy making sure my foster parents are working, I love chewing on bones or taking a nice long nap. I enjoy watching tv as I've never seen it before, and it makes a lot of funny noises.

I do require some special medication and food in order to keep me healthy, as I have some skin and food allergies. I cannot have poultry, but I have done well with a single source protein diet, such as, beef or lamb. My foster parents or the shelter can point you in the right direction for food. Something else that helps me stay healthy is a dose of Apoquel daily. This medication keeps me from itching all day long and lets me focus on what I do best - naps and chewing on bones.

Jake's adoption fee is fully sponsored, and he is neutered, microchipped and current on all vaccines.

If you are interested in adopting please go to our website at www.partnersforpetsil.org/applications and fill out an online application.

animal.description:
Hey it’s me Cerberus and I weigh 103 lbs! 
I like long walks on the beach and .... just kidding but I do like going for walks. I like to walk right beside my person when I’m on a leash because it’s too hard to pull them around everywhere (and besides, my foster brother’s got that one covered).  I am also really good at staying with my hoomans when I don’t have a leash on.  It’s nice when I get to run ahead a bit but they’re slow so I come back to make sure they’re staying beside me! Also, wherever I am in the house or outside as soon as I hear my person make a noise, even if it’s not my name, I go see what they need. 
I looooooove getting pets, but ONLY from my person/people.  If I don’t know you I’ll get scared and I’m not really sure why.  It took a day or two for them to trust me and me to trust them, I guess I kinda like when people play hard to get.  After they ignored me for a bit I decided they were ok and I would try to cuddle with them because that’s what I really want.  Now I’m so glad they still want to pet me even after I snapped because I think it’s my favourite thing! 
I usually get extra goodies on my breakfast which I think is great! Apparently it’s to help get muscles on my back legs. Maybe it’ll help me when I need to turn quick, because sometimes my feet get tangled now. 
Another thing I love is car rides! I get so excited when I hear the keys jingle, it’s sooo relaxing, I just find a spot near the back window to lay down and I stay there until it’s time to get out. 
I am already around 7 years old so even though I like being outside, I don’t have as much energy as those crazy puppies so it’s nice when we can just lay around the house too!  I am really good in the house. I find my spot and lay down when you’re busy, but if you’re not I’ll come over for cuddles. I am fully house trained.  The first couple days in my foster house I was stressed out and I didn’t know how to say I needed to go out so I had a couple accidents but i haven’t done that since the first day.  
I really like my foster brother and want to play but I think he’s scared of me because I’m so big.  I don’t really know how to ask him to play because I didn’t grow up with dogs.  I’ve found out that toys are really fun though! 
I’ve met a bunch of dogs so far and I just sniff them and continue what I’m doing.  There was one dog who stressed me out but he was super hyper and wouldn’t stop bugging me to play with him.  I don’t get mad though I just found a spot away from him. 
Im good with cats and was ok with the shitzu I met. I tried to sniff her and she nipped my nose. 

I don’t like new people touching me and will let you know when I’m comfortable with touch. I do have a bite history but I am not mean, I was simply scared and confused. 

My foster mom says I’m a king, I think it’s because I’m super important and she gives me treats and toys and loves me, it might be because of the kind of dog I am too, I might be mixed with other things but I look mostly like a king shepherd.  
I am really big and can be clumsy so it would be best if I don’t go to a house with kids. 

Cerberus is a gentle giant, but requires patience at first.  He is known to nip at hands and does not like being pet until he fully trusts you. If you are the right person for Cerberus, it will be important to let other people know not to put their hands out towards him.  He doesn’t mind being walked by new people, or having other people in the house, he’d just prefer to be ignored by everyone other than his trusted people or person.  He is up to date on his shots and was very recently neutered. He will be your best friend, he just needs someone who will commit to giving him a couple days to get used to new people and places.

4champanimalrescue.com

animal.description:
Meet Opal!

Opal is such a sweetheart and loves everyone she meets!    She knows to sit for treats, she is a smart girl and eager to please. Opal has been in the shelter since 6/19/2020.  Opal needs to be an only pet, she does not get along with other dogs and will not be cat friendly.   She loves attention and will be a fantastic companion to a lucky family.  She has a routine of coming into the office daily when she gets walked, she knows where the treat bowl is at and comes in and waits for her treat.

Opal would be best in a home with older children or only adults as she tends to jump and does not know her size.  She just needs a loving family that will be willing to work with her on her manners. 

Opal weighs 65 lbs, she has been spayed, she is heartworm free, current on all of her vaccinations, flea/tick prevention, and she is microchipped. 

Opal stays in a shelter in Mississippi, she is available for a virtual meet and greet as well as more videos and photos are available upon request.

******IMPORTANT - PLEASE READ ALL THE GREAT INFO BELOW******

***Please don't apply unless you are very serious about adopting, and are ready to move forward with the adoption process. We are super busy and make a great effort to respond back to EVERYONE ASAP! WHEN WE TAKE THE TIME TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION AND RESPOND BACK TO THE APPLICANT JUST TO BE EITHER IGNORED OR BE TOLD THEY CANNOT COME FOR SEVERAL DAYS, MORE TIME IS WASTED~PLEASE HAVE MORE RESPECT THAN THAT!

PLEASE read our website's ADOPTION PROCESS PAGE prior to submitting an adoption application. www.apupspizzazzrescue.com/adoption-process 
ADOPTION APPLICATION: www.apupspizzazzrescue.com/adoption-application 

ABOUT OUR RESCUE DOGS: 
 All of our dogs are located in Connecticut, are spayed or neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, have been given deworming medications, and have had CT State health checks, & go home with a leash, collar, & packet of medical paperwork. 

BREED IDENTIFICATION:
Please understand that many rescue dogs are mixes of multiple breeds. Petfinder allows us to choose up to two breeds per dog. While the shelters and our rescue do our best in accurately identifying breeds, breed identification is not guaranteed. If there is a certain breed that you do not want, it is very important that you share this with our rescue when applying. When adopting a puppy, breed uncertainty plays a big part in the size/look of the dog as an adult. Please know that any puppy can be a wonderful dog, regardless of preconceived notions of certain breeds, but it is very important that the adopter has the dedication and patience to raise the puppy with boundaries, consistency, structure, & love. The more effort you give towards training & time you allow for exercise, your puppy will grow to be a HUGE source of UNCONDITIONAL LOVE, TOTAL LOYALTY, HAPPINESS, COMFORT & COMPANIONSHIP!

ABOUT OUR RESCUE:
We are a small rescue run by volunteers & focused on finding the right match for both our dogs & for you. If you are interested in adopting through our rescue, you first will need to complete an adoption application & be approved as a potential adopter before meeting any of our pups. No need to be intimidated by our application as it allows us to get to know you & your lifestyle. Of course, the more you can share the better! Please also note, while a fenced yard is fantastic, it is not required by our rescue, however, it may be required for a certain dog occasionally.  Once adoption applicants are approved to become potential adopters, we offer private appointments where you can meet one or several dogs at the discretion of the rescue. We offer a unique & pleasant experience focused on finding the perfect match. It is extremely important to us that everyone is treated with respect & that NO ONE IS LEFT HANGING. WE WILL GET BACK TO YOU WITHIN 2 TO 3 DAYS of application submission. If there is a dog you are eager to meet, please  TEXT US DIRECTLY at 203-241-2351 so that we can check the status of your application and move it forward immediately. We look forward to hearing from you and helping you find your new best friend.

*All adult dogs can be cat tested by request.

HOME/RENTER INSURANCE:
SOME PROVIDERS HAVE VERY STRICT POLICIES REGARDING WHICH TYPE OF DOG BREEDS ARE ALLOWED UNDER THEIR COVERAGE. STATE FARM WAS SUGGESTED TO US AS THEY DO NOT PUNISH, DROP, NOR REFUSE YOU DUE TO DOG BREED SHOULD YOU RUN INTO ISSUES WITH YOUR CURRENT PROVIDER.

animal.description:
Diamond came to us from a shelter in North Carolina. She was found as a stray so we don’t know her history. However, she was clearly someone’s indoor pet as she knows what a couch is and wants to snuggle with her people.  She is also fully housebroken and also does not try to take things off of counters.  She loves to be pet and will nudge people when they stop petting her, as if to say, “Hey, Keep going!”  She is super quiet and for that reason is a great option for a family that lives in a condo or townhouse type of setting.  She rarely makes a sound!  She does not require a fenced yard as she is perfectly content burning off energy by playing with her stuffed toys.  By playing with them, that means shredding them and pulling all the stuffing out.  Once the toy is de-stuffed, she will toss around the remains of her stuffie as if it is a new toy.  She is currently being leash walked to go potty in a yard a few times a day, then getting a walk of about 20 minutes at night and that is perfectly fine with Diamond.  She does not need a big yard to exercise in.

She is a big, strong girl who is estimated to be about 3 years old.   She does not realize how big and clumsy she is and for that reason she is likely not a fit for a home with young kids.  She also is not a great leash walker and thinks that when out on her potty walks at night she is supposed to zigzag her way up the street, pulling in every direction.  She is super strong but is expected to learn to walk better on her walks with practice and time.  She loves going for car rides and would make a great road tripping companion.

The shelter had taken her into the room where the cats were housed and she was described as curious, especially when a cat was trying to paw at her.  Her current foster home does not have any cats so they have not been able to more thoroughly see how she reacts to a cat. However, on a walk she did see an outdoor cat and was excited, but in a playful way. As for dogs, she definitely seems like she wants to play, but she is somewhat overly excited when first seeing other dogs, and the other dogs that she has encountered seem to be taken back by her over exuberant way of wanting to meet. For that reason, we think that most dogs may not be as fond of her as she seems to want to be of them.  That is just fine with Diamond as she is perfectly happy hanging with her people at home and not necessarily needing a canine companion.

He will just cower in fear and try and retreat from men he meets at first.  But with some chicken and steak he is learning that guys are not so bad.   Riley would do best in a quiet home where he can settle himself and get all the love and snooze time he deserves.   He is good with other dogs in playgroups at his current foster home but if a dog confronts him or gets an attitude with him he will not back down.  Therefore we prefer a home where he can be the only dog. Adoption fee 100.00

Hi, my name is Cammie, and I'm a beautiful two year old GSD who was transferred to FRGSR after my former owner surrendered me because she was moving. Prior to this, we were best buddies and did everything together, so as you might guess, I'm feeling a little lost with all the recent changes in my life. If you're that special person, please go to adoptagsd.org and submit an online application. My adoption fee is $350.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

If you are reading about Wilson on a website other than Bfpa.org, please go directly to Bfpa.org since it will tell you more about him than what is listed on other adoption sites. All dogs posted on our website ARE available.

You MUST submit an application at

BFPA.org

if you are interested in Wilson!

FOSTER COMMENTS:

Wilson is a 55-60lb German Shepard mix, whose favorite things to do are, sleep, sunbathe and take car rides! He is estimated to be about 8 years old.

Wilson is very chill. He does whine when he sees other dogs and doesn't get along with all dogs. He probably would do best being an only dog in a home where a human is home most of the time

He had not been exposed to cats prior to his foster placement with us. When he first arrived he was curious and approached with ease. He still demonstrates an interest in "checking her out" every so often when she is in proximity.

We do not have young children, our youngest is 19. In general, I have not noticed any nervous tendencies with people, and I think Wilson would be fine with children.

Wilson is house trained, and we take him out every few hours. While we have a crate for him, we have not used it with him because he has great house manners. When we leave the house he has remained out of a crate with our other 2 dogs in the house. There have been no issues and at this point, we have been away as long as 3 to 3 1/2 hours. At night, Wilson sleeps on his dog bed on the floor of our room right next to his foster sister and brother. Wilson has gone about 10 hours through the night and a few 6 hour stretches during the day. He is not a great fan of the rain, so he has chosen to hold himself until it stops or is a little less heavy. He also recently demonstrated a need to go out to the bathroom by waiting at the door we use to go out.

Wilson is pretty low key. He likes to spend time outdoors "hanging out" and enjoying the sun. A fenced yard is required for Wilson so that he is able to hang out, enjoy the weather and have some playtime with a human or dog friend. He tends to spend a big part of his day sleeping. He does like a walk but doesn't demand one. Wilson walks very well in his harness on a leash. However, when he can become fixated on a scent or a dog in his vicinity. He doesn't want to keep walking and sometimes requires moving him away from the fixation.

Wilson is a great dog and needs an equally great forever home. He does enjoy his human companionship and often stays nearby, either on a his comfy dog bed, an office chair with a view, or even cozying up next to you on the couch! Wilson is a very sweet, handsome, easy going boy who needs a forever home to call his own.

EVERY DOG HAS A STORY: Wilson was found as a stray and taken to a rural shelter. No one claimed him so BFPA was happy to admit him into our rescue. BFPA is now trying to find the perfect home for him. Does your home sound like the perfect one?

Some of the information contained in this biography includes approximations based on our expertise and is not guaranteed.

Applicants must live no further than one hour from Cary NC as our dogs must be seen by a BFPA veterinarian for all medical care prior to adoptions being finalized. Our foster guardians deliver dogs to their new homes for adoption trials and we do home visits to finalize all adoptions. We therefore require applicants to live within an hours drive of Cary NC.

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING WILSON ? If so, please fill out our dog adoption application by copying and pasting this link in a new browser window:

https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/of/f?c=WHMSYCNC

animal.description:
Spot is another special rescue from the amazing Rescue Nowzad in Kabul Afghanistan.   Spot is 6 years old and was rescued years ago off the war-torn streets in that area.   He comes to us now for finding his forever home in the United States.  Adoption fee 200.00 - ******UPDATE 1/27 FROM FOSTER PARENTS:  Spot is learning to do his business outside and doing well.  He is very leary of having his neck touched and having a collar put on him.   This is probably b/c he was just with a pack of dogs never on leash at the shelter he came from for so many years.  He is timid with new people and surroundings but adjusting well slowly but surely.
A fenced in yard is needed for him and an adult only home with possibly only older teenagers due to his timid nature and being hand shy.  Prior dog ownership required and a laid back more submissive dog as a companion would be good for him.  We were told at the Nowzad shelter that he liked to be the dominant dog.

animal.description:
So let's first address the elephant in the room...This boy's ears were mutilated and up until rescue, he was treated like garbage. He was picked up wandering the road by a nice police officer who took him to a small, neighboring municipal shelter, where he first received care. He was defeated, severely emaciated (see photo of him wearing a harness), scarred and terrified. The shelter reached out to us and it was there he earned the name Cowboy, because cowboys have to be tough, especially when no one is looking.

After a brief stint at the vet, Cowboy gained some weight, was neutered and made up to date on all shots. He is now in foster care where he quickly learned that he enjoys a nice, soft place to lay, he will never again go hungry, and the backyard is for playing or simply hanging out with friends. Even though his advocates are dismayed by his past mistreatment, Cowboy harbors no ill-will toward anyone and is just about the sweetest boy we have ever met.

Cowboy would do great in just about any home but we are not sure he is appropriate with small kids and/or cats because he has not been observed in that situation. Cowboy is still gaining weight and will get bigger, although he seems unaware of his large size. Cowboy requires a quiet place to eat and a slow feeder bowl. That's about the extent of the special care he'll need. He is crate/doggy door trained, and gets along with other dogs with proper introduction. He is learning simple commands but sometimes gets over excited at treat time so he just needs to be reminded to be ”nice”. We think Cowboy is about one and half years old so he still has a little playful pup in him. He wants to please though so he is receptive to positive reinforcement-type training.
  
Cowboy is a quiet chap but will alert you of any unknown sounds. He loves to just hang out and chill after some exercise. Have you ever wanted a dog as a best friend? A dog that will follow you everywhere and dote on you?  A dog that wants to be close to you as you sleep? Watch a movie? Do laundry, wash dishes, etc...? How about a dog that snores?  He has the cutest snore and we especially love his liver colored nose! Cowboy's eyes are dreamy too and almost match his coat, which feels like velvet. We hope that one day his velvety fur will grow in enough to help cover his scars.

We know that his adopter will be unfairly saddled with a sort of stigma attached to his appearance. We also know, from experience, that adopters of previously mutilated dogs like Cowboy are accepting of that burden and often, unintentionally serve as an ambassador for the breed and rescue in general. The reward though, is having such a loyal, true blue friend that thinks you hang the moon. With that, you have Cowboy.

If you would like to be considered as an adoption candidate, please submit an application through our website. His adoption fee is $200.

www.NinjaPawsRescue.org

Hi, my name is Maxie! I have all the energy, curiosity and spunk of a typical puppy. I love chewing on my toys, I'm learning to fetch, and enjoy a daily visit or two to the dog park (where I am working on my socialization skills). I adore naps, snuggles, belly rubs and am happy for attention from kids and adults alike.

I am kenneled trained but do fine when left out alone. I am also house trained and can make it through the night without having to go out. I love meal time (and treats) and will hang with you whenever you are in the kitchen - but I really don't "beg" for food.

I hope for a home where people are around a lot and can find time throughout the day to play, rub and snuggle with me. A home with another dog would be great (I am not sure about cats as I don't have much experience with them, but my fosters think I would be okay because I'm so chill). Apply today to meet me!

Date of birth (estimated):
7/10/20

Good with Dogs: Yes

Good with Cats: Unknown

House Trained: Yes

Adoption Fee:

$500

If you are interested in meeting or adopting this animal, please read the following before submitting an adoption application on our website - fureverhomerescue.com.

Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate vaccinations, 4Dx test (covers tick-borne diseases (Anaplasmosis , Lymes, Ehrlichiosis) as well as heart worm) & de-worming. We ask that our dogs live indoors unless otherwise stated & agreed upon. Applicants must live in MN within a reasonable distance from the Twin Cities Metro Area. We do not adopt out of state.

animal.description:
All ARCBCR dogs are spayed or neutered, up to date on all vaccines, heartworm negative and on preventative, dewormed and on flea and tick preventative before going to their forever homes.If interested in this pup, please fill out an online application on our website, www.arcbcr.org, and an ARC volunteer will contact you regarding your home evaluation to see if you and this pet are a good match.Please consider making a donation to help the ARCBCR Border Collies.  ARCBCR is a 501(c)3 organization making your donation eligible as a tax deduction.  

Adoption Application: http://www.arcbcr.org/apply-to-adopt/

Meet Jingle! Jingle is a sweet, handsome Border Collie/Lab mix that is approximately 1 year old and weighs about 37 pounds.  

We don’t know much about Jingle’s past, but we think he probably didn’t have the best life before becoming part of the ARCBCR family. ARCBCR first learned of Jingle when he was dumped, by his previous family, in a rural, high-kill shelter in NC. Jingle was so terrified of people when he first arrived at his foster home, that he hid in his crate too terrified to stand or walk and had to be carried in and out of the house to potty.  As terrified as he might have been, he tolerated every new and frightening interaction and never exhibited a single sign of aggression, a true sign of just how sweet his temperament is. Jingle now confidently trots out to play in the yard with his foster brothers and sisters. After a good romp he is happy to return inside to settle with a chew bone or take a nap.  

Jingle is initially a shy but friendly fellow and is still learning that humans are kind and being pet is enjoyable. He is nervous in new situations and around new people but will slowly but surely warm up especially if treats are involved. Jingle has recently started greeting his foster mom with tail wags and flopping over for belly rubs. He has gone from hiding in his crate to happily following his foster mom from room to room, curious as to what fun they will find next. He is a bit of an expert at social distancing as he enjoys being in the same room with his people, just 3’ apart. 

Jingle has learned that toys and balls are fun to play with and loves a good wrestling match with his foster brothers and sisters. He has also learned that the sound of the refrigerator door opening means all the good things! Some of his favorite treats are raw carrots, pineapple, and ice cubes! 

Jingle is house trained; crate trained and is learning to walk on a leash. On the rare occasion that he’s up to something naughty, a sharp “No” is all it takes to get his attention and redirect him. He still has some puppy tendencies like stealing dirty laundry, digging holes, and if you’ve left something tasty too close to the edge of the counter, he will surely find it.  

Jingle has come a long way in his foster home, and we’ve promised to find him the perfect forever home with a lifetime of love and gentle care. 

For that reason, he has some requirements for his new home. 

•  A home with a fully fenced yard, no apartments, and no electric fences. 

• A friendly canine buddy to romp with. A dog the same size or larger will be required as he gets rough sometimes and a smaller dog may get hurt. 

• A quieter home without a lot of comings and goings.

• A family that is home more often than not. 

• A home with no children or age 10 or older.   

Jingle will need a forever family that realizes he is a work-in-progress and is willing to gently and patiently continue to build his trust. He plays “hard-to-get” but earning his love and affection is worth the effort and wait. We feel confident that with continued love and patience, Jingle will be able to let go the hurt of his past and move on to being a happy, well-adjusted, and confident boy! 

Jingle is neutered, up to date on vaccines and is microchipped. He is being fostered near Charlotte, NC.

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!!! FOREVER HOME MUST HAVE A FRIENDLY, PLAYFUL AND CONFIDENT

MALE

RESIDENT DOG or 2 OR 3!

AWWW! LOOK AT THAT ADOGABLE FACE AND THOSE EARS HEAR EVERYTHING YOU SAY! Meet SOOKIE, a 5 month old, 42lb, Shepherd/hound looking for a new forever home with an active, experienced dog guardian, a fun-loving friendly, confident male resident dog and a large fenced in yard where they can romp and play. Her current family rescued her several months ago from a breeder situation where she was confined to a crate 24/7. Although they adore her and she knows it, she's too much puppy for their 3 y/o child and the senior dogs. She asked us to help her rehome Sookie with a family that will love her to the moon and back and give her the great life she deserves.

SOOKIE is a high energy pup who loves to play, eat and sleep and play some more. She is very smart, and highly treat and praise motivated so she responds well to force free or positive reinforcement training. She will need ongoing training and lots of playtime. Her guardian shares the following:

"Sookie is a very sweet, friendly, affectionate, loving, energetic, sometimes vocal pup. She is the smartest dog I've ever met. I took her to one training class and they had her paying attention and listening to basic commands on the first try. She loves her Kong toy and will chew it for hours. She loves to run and play. She will wrestle with my lab mix all day if he lets her. She's housebroken and crate trained. She is a puppy who wants what she wants and can still be bossy about it. She loves to dig and will chew anything she can find if not supervised. Sookie is so smart. We've been working on good house and people and dog manners and she's making progress but will need an experienced guardian willing to continue with training and get her to the finish line. She is going to make someone a fabulous dog. I can't tell you enough how smart she is.... with the right guardian, she could excel in any dog sport and learn every trick in the book. She's just a wonderful pup who deserves an awesome home with someone who will give her a great life."

SOOKIE is up to date on age-appropriate shots. She is not spayed. Her adoption fee is $575. which includes a spay/neuter fee. Please note that training is highly recommended for all young dogs.

As with all rescue animals, breed determination cannot be validated without genetic testing. Visit WWW.LULUSRESCUE.ORG for an overview of Lulu's Rescue adoption process.

Thanks for adopting and saving a life!

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Trevor! I'm a big guy looking to live a big life. My friends at ARNO are impressed with my interior design skills as I work on moving things around in my kennel to be just how I like it. animal.description:
Dashwood, or as we refer to him as Dash, was dumped on the Haven road in a horrible, makeshift crate with his siblings. He is now the last of his siblings waiting on his forever home. Because he had such a rough start to life, he is still a bit timid towards humans. He, however, is very sweet and is a melt-in-your-hands type of dog. He does best with a doggy sibling who can help him come out of his shell. He has learned to walk on a leash and makes a great walking buddy. He is still young and is going to grow to be quite a large boy. Dashwood has a bit of separation anxiety and would like to be in a home where he can be with someone all of the time. We have had volunteers of all ages around Dashwood and he is patient and kind with all. He loves snacks, especially the bacon flavored ones! We are unsure if he is potty-trained but he has been in our office for a few hours with no accidents. Dashwood is neutered, microchipped, and up to date on all shots. estimated date of birth is 10/17/19. Dash weighs 73lbs...All pets have lifetime sanctuary at Haven of the Ozarks. If they cannot remain with their adopter, they must be returned to the Haven.

Adoption fees are as follows: 
Puppies under the age of 6 months - $125

animal.description:
Chadwick was adopted when he was a young puppy and the owner thought he was cute and adorable. He is STILL cute and adorable but his owner quickly tired of having a dog and didn't spend much time with Chadwick. He spent long days outdoors while she was at work. Sometimes she would just forget him outside all night. Finally she reached out for someone to take him. Poor little guy is VERY TIMID as he hasn't experienced much in life and has never known love and affection from a human. It took him several hours to stop shaking once he got to his foster mom's house. He is beginning to settle in and is very appreciate to have the basic comforts of a warm, soft bed, nutrious food, and affection. Chadwick is very nice to the other dog in the home and has shown his apprecation to his foster by being loving and well behaved. We think Chadwick is a Chihauhua mix. His foster family has 3 other small doggies ranging from 7 to 13 years old and he enjoys their companionship. No possessiveness of food or his people. He LOVES to be a lap dog so we would like to have someone who enjoys snuggles. He is house trained and knows how to use the doggie door.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application at https://www.circle2rescue.com/dog-adoption-application/ The adoption fee of $300 includes the spay/neuter, vaccinations, deworming and microchip. 

Please note, Circle 2 Rescue cannot guarantee the breed, composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have no history prior to them entering the rescue. We make every effort to ensure the dogs are healthy.

animal.description: Oreo is already America's favorite cookie, but he would be happy to become your favorite cookie too! Oreo is a distinguished gentleman who likes a calm household. Before he came to us he had not met very many people in his life. He would greatly appreciate it if others could give him plenty of time to warm up to them. To be honest, he doesn't really like everyone he meets -- he's rather picky about humans and he is not tolerant of children. However, when he is around adults he likes then he becomes an adoring social butterfly. Just like his preference with people, Oreo also prefers only calm dogs. He would enjoy being your one and only dog, but could live with a well-matched dog friend (no cats, please!) Oreo is opinionated and well read so he hopes you enjoy random chit chats here and there. He loves walks in the park but also appreciates time to cuddle on the couch. He is always available to sample tasty snacks and is happy just to be with his person. Though he tries to hold up the reputation of a steady and well balanced gentleman, he gets lonely should you leave him so he would appreciate it if you had a more flexible schedule so he doesn't have to be alone for too long. Oreo promises to be a good co-worker and protector if you take him home. Does he sound like he has the potential to become your favorite cookie? Please inquire if you would like to join Oreo's friend circle!

animal.description: Don't be late to acquaint with Tate. He's great! He's much better than our rhymes, at least! Tate is fun, goofy youngster who is also showing us quite a bit of intelligence. He's currently residing in an APA foster home and should be ready to make the transition to your home. Tate is a real people-lover. He especially loves to cuddle up with his favorite people, and put his head on your lap or feet. He likes to follow his fosters around the house so that he doesn't miss out on anything interesting. But he's also showed us signs of being a serious student. He's quickly learned commands such as stay, sit, lie down, stand up, turn around, back up, roll over, and look at me. He is treat-motivated so he's been easy to train. He also does well in a crate. We're also seeing improvement in his leash manners. Tate enjoys going for walks and has been learning to focus on his handler. He should make a great walking (or running) partner. With treat-based reward training he should continue to make strides! Before arriving at the shelter, Tate doesn't appear to have had any experience with toys - but now that he's getting the hang of it he is starting to entertain himself. He likes to chew on Kongs and is learning to play fetch. He'll burn off some calories as he learns to play new games with his family! But for a younger dog he is fairly mellow. He follows his family's energy level. He'll spend plenty of time curled up on the couch with you. Tate has a comical nature that should keep a smile on everyone's face. He would love to be the only dog in the home, with a family that can establish a routine for him that contains training, exercise, and affection. This dog has all the makings of a great long-term companion for a lucky family! And remember that when you adopt from APA you're not only giving Tate a home, you're also allowing a second dog to join us.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m just so happy to meet you! I’m Rodger, and I am a handsome whirlwind of my species. Meaning, I like to explore, I have lots of energy, I like to give every human and fellow canine a friendly hello, I can jump tall fences, I love walks, I like stealing shoes and pillows, I jump up on kitchen counters if you let me and hey, did I mention I’m a whirlwind? Yeah, that’s me, alright. But I also like to snuggle, curl up in a comfy spot, and my foster mum says I’m a real quick learner, too. Is there anything I don’t like? Well, being left alone for starters – that’s just scary and oh-so-boring! I like being near you! Not too keen on crates, I must say. And yeah, these wheely things, my foster humans call them bicycles – I like chasing them. Oh wait, we’re back to what I like! Well, if you like me, then let’s make a deal, shall we? I’ll be part of your family, and you let me do (almost) all the things I like. I’d like that!

animal.description:
We rescued Angel baby from the shelter 2 months ago. This is why we do what we do! For these precious faces! I took a chance on her when the shelter reached out to us to help her. Angel was one of the lucky ones out of the bunch we took in at the end of the year. This poor girl was treated like trash! She was neglected, abused, skinny, malnourished, and used for breeding. She had puppies recently which unfortunately all ended up dying. If you look at the pictures you can see what condition she was in and how she came to us. Just breaks your heart! Her skin was a mess and her eyes were so shut down. She had a huge gash on her head. Her boobs were still big full of milk. She had cuts, bites, scars, and sores all over her. I can’t imagine the previous life she had. Humans did this to her!

I have been fostering Angel for 2 months now and I’m finally getting to know her personality. Her eyes have life now! She is absolutely precious and so sweet! Angel doesn’t let her past get in her way! She’s full of confidence and so loving with people! Her skin has healed up and she has gained weight! She is actually a healthy dog now! Angel has gotten along with every dog I’ve had her around. She has acclimated with my pack so good. She listens well and perfectly crate trained. Every day we are working with her and getting her ready for a bright future. 

Angel is a 4 year old pit bull mix with cropped ears. She’s around 60ish lbs now that she’s gained weight. Angel would benefit in a active home with other dogs. No cats. She loves car rides and going on adventures. Angel is ready to start meeting potential adopters. If you are interested in sweet Angel please send us a detailed email and request a application! Must be home owners with a fully fenced in yard and have bully breed experience. She is fostered in Sacramento and we only adopt locally in Northern California.

animal.description:
Meet Odin in Colorado!!!!

This dashingly handsome guy is Odin, and he is AMAZING!!! Besides his good looks he also has a loving personality and he adores his people. One of his favorite things is when his humans rub his belly and his tail just goes thump thump thump as he enjoys the attention. 

Odin is a big guy at 110 pounds, and he’s healthy as a horse. He still has some energy for a 7 year old large breed dog and does best when he can get out for some exercise and mental stimulation everyday. 

Odin has lived with other dogs, but does seem to want to be the top dog. He also tends to guard his food so if he goes to a home with another dog that will need to be managed. He would do best in a mature household without cats. 

We think Odin would be in heaven if he got adopted by an active person who is looking for a best buddy to have adventures with, and then chill out at home with afterwards. And who wouldn’t want such an amazing best friend?

We are partnering with Big Bones Canine Rescue to find a loving forever home for Odin. If you are interested please email us at woof@olddogsnewdigs.com and we will get you pointed in the right direction. And please help us get the word out about Odin and share share share!!!!!

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

animal.description: Hello, my name is Huck! I was surrendered because I needed some medical care and my family needed help caring for me. I didn't always get along with the other male dog in my home but I would frequently go next door to play with the girl dog over there. I should not be around cats or other small animals. I have been friendly to all of the people I have met in the shelter. All of the volunteers enjoy taking me out on walks because I walk nicely on my leash. Please keep checking my profile for updates as the staff gets to know me better! If this dog has been successful in our play groups it is not a guarantee that a dog will be social with other dogs in their home or in public settings. Dogs are individuals and have personality conflicts, just like us. Play groups do not guarantee that territorial or resource guarding issues will not surface in the home. While play groups do help us get to know the dog's better, once they are adopted their new environments and new relationships will influence their behavior in ways we cannot predict. The Adoption Fee Includes: - initial canine distemper combination vaccination - first worming or stool check - rabies vaccination (for animals over 3 months of age) - AVID microchipping - flea treatment/preventative - spaying or neutering Adoption fee: $95.00 Per state law, ALL ADOPTERS must purchase a non-refundable 2021 dog license at time of adoption for any canine three months and older. The cost of the license is $7.00. (Senior Citizen or Person with Disability-$5.00) Leash and collar included.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Goliath

Goliath is an English Mastiff that came to us from a shelter Apparently he was in a high kill shelter in Texas and was transported to Washington and then Portland to a shelter where we got him from. We have no history on him. His age is a guess.

He is a very sweet senior boy that doesn't get along with other dogs or cats. He is housetrained, does well on walks, and loves car rides.

Goliath takes thyroid medication twice a day and will need to have his thyroid checked every 6 months.

Because of the lack of history on him, he will only be placed with older children.

If you are interested in Goliath or any of our fosters, please go to our website at www.mastiffrescueoregon.org, click on adoption info, and submit an application online. Meet and greets will not be done without an application on file.

Our fosters are in private residences. Please do not call prior to 8;00am or after 8:00pm

VERNA LOUISE

Verna Louise is 3 1/2 years old and may be a Golden Doodle (but her face looks like an Irish Wolfhound). This friendly girl is about 55-60 lbs, She is about the size of a short standard poodle.  She IS a barker but a collar that beeps then vibrates can be used and she won’t bark as much...except at her toy balls! She WANTS her balls!!!

This beautiful girl is REALLY a happy puppy, but needs to be an only dog. Verna is a a wonderful, affectionate, happy, energetic dog that needs a loving, active family. She needs to be in a house without other dogs or cats. She loves to play fetch and usually has a ball in her mouth. She rides great in a car.

She has gone through basic and intermediate training at the Complete Canine with Jeremy Brown and passed with flying colors. She knows hand signals and will respond immediately to them. She's also had snake training.

Verna is a Doodle and will need periodic grooming. 

You must have a secure, fenced yard, and the time to train a puppy. These bigger breeds have endless energy when they are young. They must be exercised to be healthy & mentally stable nice dogs. This dog must be walked or taken to a dog park every day. They are working dogs, and if they don't have a job, they will find one, like dismantling your couch.
Not trying to scare you away, but if your energy is limited PLEASE adopt an older more placid dog. If you are gone more than four hours a day this dog is not for you. 

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rottie & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

We do adopt out of area under the right circumstances. If you are willing to travel to Tucson to meet us, and to personally transport your adopted pet home, we may be willing to work with you. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secured, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Verna Louise or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, groomed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.

animal.description:
This handsome boy is Will. He was a stray in TN that was being fed by volunteers. He was eventually rescued and placed in a foster homer. Initially, he was malnourished with little energy, but with good food training and TLC, he is definitely flourishing and coming into his own.

Will is very sweet and just adores love and attention. His foster is home most of the time and has been working with him daily and he has adapted well to his new life as an indoor pet.
Will would do best with a home where his people can spend a lot of time with him. Another dog would be recommended as he enjoys their companionship and loves to play. 

Will does show some resource food guarding with other dogs, so would need to fed separately. After being in the situation he was in, this is to be expected. Will is otherwise friendly with other dogs, shares toys and loves to run and play in the yard. Will would do better with dogs of his same personality/activity level, we would like him to be adopted to a home with another dog.

Will did test positive for heartworm and has begun pre-treatment. PAWS will guide you through his treatment (and of course, foot the bill). This will require you to live somewhat near to one of our partner vets that administer the treatment.

Will is crate trained and will go into his crate and sleeps in his crate at night, but does have to be bribed and nudged to go in, as he prefers to stay by his people. No accidents in the crate. He is progressing well with housetraining, but still needs to be taken out for his potty breaks and encouraged. 
He also does well on a leash with minimal pulling.

Check out will playing with his foster sibling: 
https://youtu.be/Or-SAqkIV4E
 
Apply today for this striking boy!

Name: Will
Breed: Terrier Mix
Sex: Male
Age: 2-3 yrs old (estimate)
Weight: 57 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: Yes, 1/13/21
Vaccinations: UTD
Heartworm: Positive, started treatment 1/7/21
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Has been around a 7 and 9yr old but not lived with them.
Good with Dogs: Yes, a canine sibling is recommended since Will loves to play. 
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.

NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is PEANUT, I'm a sweet Australian Cattle Dog/Blue Heeler mix looking for a FurEver home. Here's what my foster mom has to say about me! Apply to meet me at tailsandtrails.org!

Peanut aka Buddy has made tremendous progress in his first week with his foster family. After a rough start as one of the ""Tennessee Treasures"", he is learning to be a puppy. With no prior exposure to treats, toys and snuggles, he has quickly learned to love all three. Buddy is crate trained and will often take a break in his crate where he stashes all his toys! He is working hard on housebreaking and is most reliable if taken outside on a frequent schedule. He has mastered ""Sit"" and is working on ""Down"", ""Fetch"" and walking on a leash. He is an old soul in a puppy's body and often chooses to sit quietly and observe especially in new situations. He gets along well with his rat terrier and Aussie sisters and Aussie brother. He is very curious, but gentle with the farm cats. While comfortable in the house, he is still timid about being outside with new smells and sounds. It helps to have a fellow dog out with him. His owner will need to be consistent with his outside experiences - using the same door, taking him to a regular area to relieve himself. Buddy needs time to feel comfortable in a new environment. Inside, he is a curious puppy, but he responds well when asked to leave something alone. Buddy loves a good spa treatment including bath and nail trim. He gets along well with his human siblings and their teenage friends. He has shown no aggression with food, toys or strangers and is normally very quiet. While cautious and quiet in nature, Buddy still loves to play and be a puppy.

animal.description:
Meet Teddy!

Hey there, hi there, ho there, my name is Teddy, just like a bear. Oh, that rhymes! I'm 10 years old and just 51 pounds, so not super big, which is not very bear like. I'm a real good boy around older kids, but the little ones are just too much for me. I do okay around female dogs who aren't going to be in my face and will give me my space. Please no male dogs though, I'm not very fond of them. Foster mom says although she introduced me to a cat, she can't say that I could live with one. I'm very hyper focused on them, and I would hate to be put in a situation where I would ever hurt anything. I would do perfectly fine in a home where I get all the attention and love from my humans, you know, their one and only. I'm mostly housetrained, but I will need a bit of help with knowing what's expected of me, and being taught that marking things in my new home isn't okay. Luckily, you can put a belly band on me until I know that's not acceptable. I just need my new people to be patient and show me the ropes of my new home!

I'm a gentle, easy going guy who likes going for walks or just hanging out in the back yard with my family. If you have a fenced yard I'd love to play with you or your human friends while you cook out on warm summer nights. I'm pretty social eith all the humans I meet, so I'll be sure to keep your friends company! I can't wait for my new humans to take me home so we can start being a forever family!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply
