animal.description:
Molly is an affectionate, spunky, responsive Border Collie who is about two and a half years old.  She is smart as a whip and will benefit from some positive reinforcement training.  Molly walks fairly well on a leash already.

We are still assessing Molly's compatibility with other dogs.  As can be seen in the attached video she is perfectly friendly with the pitbull she is currently living with.  However, other introductions have been sketchy.  We will update this profile when we learn more. Currently, we are looking for a foster home without other dogs.  Molly loves people!

Her ideal home would provide her with the exercise, enrichment, and mental engagement she craves. She's a touch overweight so needs some physical conditioning, and a foster guardian who is home the majority of the time.  She is dedicated to the fetch game!  If you have a fenced yard big enough to throw a ball, she'd be happy to play fetch 4 or 5 times a day as an adjunct to her other exercise and enrichment.  

This girl needs an active home. Our best guess is that she could become neurotic, destructive and/or misbehaved if left alone or confined for long periods, under-exercised, or not provided with enough enrichment.  A home with Border Collie experience would be a plus, as would a family interested in outdoor adventure or a dog sport such as agility, obedience training, nose work, rally, treibball, (or really any dog sport).

True to her breed, she can be a little nibbly and nippy - she occasionally takes a treat hard - a habit that is easy to reverse but we wouldn't feel comfortable placing her in a home with young children.

If you think you can help with Molly, please fill out our application found here:

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

Please note, our application to foster and to adopt are the SAME - just adapt your answers accordingly.

If you have questions, email us at connellpetrescue@gmail.com

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Molly's prey drive is intact and strong.  She would likely chase any small animals she encounters.

animal.description:
At 9 years old and 30 pounds, Bonnie is still very much a vibrant girl and the perfect medium size.

She is amazing with kids and very fun to play with. At first, Bonnie can be shy when it comes to other dogs but after a few minutes, she will eventually play with them. I would like to say that Bonnie would be good with cats too if introduced properly, but I have not personally seen an interaction. 

Thankfully, she is potty trained and kennel trained, plus actually loves to be inside it during bad weather, it gives her comfort within her own space. 

Bonnie loves a good adventure and can lead/guide you on walks or walk beside you, depending on the manner that you allow her to have, she will comply. 

Bonnie’s ideal family is someone who likes to go on long walks, run (exercise) with her, a huge backyard and who are very loving and understanding to her needs. She ask for a lot of love and attention. She would be perfect with growing kids/teenagers to keep her company. 

I would not recommend a home without a backyard, no to tiny spaces and no to elderly people. Her perfect family would be perfect with someone that has a huge yard for her to run in and exhaust her energy. 

Let us know if you have more questions and want to meet Bonnie!

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Leon is one of a kind! This big Doberman is FULL of personality. He's friendly with everyone he meets and is quite affectionate (his signature move is to nudge or poke you with his nose until you pet him). Leon is incredibly smart, too. He learns quickly and will sit, lay down, roll over, and play dead on command. Of course, he's also smart enough to "train" his humans to do what HE wants, and would be most successful with an experienced owner who will continue his obedience training. Leon enjoys playing with friendly dogs--he is most compatible with rough-and-tumble females and sometimes clashes with other strong-willed male dogs. Leon walks well on leash, is good with kids, and enjoys spending time indoors with his favorite people.

Due to Leons size and rough and rowdy play style, he is not recommended to live with small dogs, and no cats as he loves to chase them.

Breed experience is recommended for this wonderful boy.

animal.description:
Name: Howie
Breed: Doberman Mix
Age: 1 Year
Sex: Male
Weight: 75 lbs. 
Before OMD: Found as a stray and did a short stint at the city shelter until his hold was up and he became a part of our crew. 
Energy Level: High, but nothing that can't be worked out with a few walks, some backyard play time, and an occasional stuffed toy. 
Snuggle Level: Equally high but only after a serious play session and a sprint (or ten) around the yard. 
Smarty Pants Level: You guessed it....high again. His foster dad says he's unbelievably intelligent and he has never seen a dog learn so fast! 
Words to describe him: Gentle. Athletic. Loyal. Affectionate. Silly. Handsome. Smart.
What we love most: He has a heart of gold. He is always happy. He will do anything just to sit at your feet or by your side and put his head in your lap. He forgets how leggy he is, gets excited and occasionally trips over himself (#doofusalert)
What he loves most: All types of food, broccoli and carrots included. Any kind of treat. Big bacon fan. His stuffed donut. His dinosaur toy. Walks. Playing in the yard. Cuddling up with his foster dad. Sharing the bed with his foster bro. Watching the world from the window. 
Life goal: Toss up...find a buffet and eat to his heart’s content or make a living as a professional cuddler.
What he knows: Sit. Down. Paw. Plus he barks to let you know when he needs to go out or when he wants to come back in.
What he’s working on: Being patient. Reigning in his exuberance when he’s excited, especially over food.
Claim to fame: He learned his commands in less than 24 hours!
Kids: Yes, but dog-savvy, sturdy kiddos only! He is gentle with little ones but he is still a puppy in a big ol’ body!
Dogs: Definitely! Though he’s more content being part of a smaller pack in a home (he adores his Lab mix foster brother) vs. a large, high-energy pack in a daycare or dog park setting. He also prefers to not share his food with other dogs (we don’t blame him!) 
Cats: No problem. He’s made friends with the cat in his foster home and happily shares his space.
Housebroken: Yep! 
Crate Trained: Sure is!
Wish List: A multi-person home (the more attention the better) with a big backyard and another animal friend or two. Active humans who are equally dedicated to outside adventures and Netflix and chill (with Howie on the couch or in bed).
Howie is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative and microchipped. He’s available for adoption to residents of CT and surrounding states. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application from Omdrescue.org.

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Tucker! Here is his video collage in NC:

https://youtu.be/O6gmsGJLkZc

Tucker is 2 years old (approx. DOB 12-15-18), male, 57 lbs., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. Tucker was found as a homeless stray in North Carolina. Vet conveyed Tucker has some sort of old injury and has an odd stance in his hind end but it does not bother him.

IN HIS CURRENT DAYCARE/BOARDING ENVIRONMENT (we make no guarantees starting over in a new dynamic):

Good with Dogs? Yes

Good with Cats? Unknown

Has a prey drive? Haven't witnessed any prey drive

Good with smaller kids (mouthy, nippy, jumpy, chase, scared)? Older kids, playful but wobbly

Energy Level (low, low-medium, medium, medium-high, or high)? Medium

Scared of people or socially outgoing? Outgoing but scared in new situations

Needs another dog in the home (if scared of people), ok as only, or either way? Either way

Crate trained? Yes

Does he like the crate? Good in crate

Potty trained? Clean in crate

Separation Anxiety from people when left alone? No

Vocal? No quieter boy

Behavior on leash when walking near lots of people/dogs? Ok on leash; pulls a little

Concerning behavior: back end wobbly, possibly old injury, does not need medical attention, doesn't hinder him, super cute

Best in the busy City or rural calm or doesn't matter? Rural probably best

He was incredibly scared at the shelter. Stay tuned for more information as Tucker s a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Tucker please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
MEDICAL HOLD ----  

Meet Lady! She was found as a stray and has several things going on that have to be taken care of prior to her being available for adoption. Lady has a severe fungal infection, osteomyelitis legions in both front legs that are causing her to limp, and then on top of all that she has the papilloma virus. The papilloma virus caused her to have warts on her body and in her mouth. She is going to be on antibiotics and injections 3 times a week, that will hopefully enable her immune system to fight off the papilloma virus and the warts will go away. The papilloma virus is contagious to other dogs but not to humans. 

We have to say that even with everything going on she is one of the sweetest and happy boxer girls you could ever meet.  She is housebroken and very calm. She is going to be starting special meds to help that we had to get compounded.  

If you are interested in Lady when she is available for adoption, please reach out to Barbara at BarbaraABoxer@gmail.com. 

Lady
Female
Age: 3/4
Dogs: Males Only 
Cats: Unknown
Kids: 10+

Heartworm Prevention is given on the 16th of each month

Popeye is one of our newest arrivals to CTDR. He was as a stray on the streets of North Texas and taken to a local shelter. CTDR was contacted when no one came to get him and we immediately went and got him. He is a beautiful double dapple boy. He was born with one eye, which is a trait of the Double Dapple breeding. He is up to date with all of his vaccines and will be neutered this coming week.
He is a very friendly to people and a very playful chap with the other dogs. He is house broken, rides well in the car and knows his way around a doggie door. His tail is always wagging and he loves to snuggle next to you under a blanket on the sofa or in the big bed. His one beautiful blue eye is working great but he likes you to approach slowly on the left side.
If you are interested in giving Popeye his forever home, please complete an application at ctdr.org.

animal.description:
Millie
1 - 2 years old (This is the vet’s guess based on her teeth)
6 lbs
Chihuahua (This is our best guess, again we don’t know for sure, since she was a street dog)


Other Dogs: She is okay with dogs, but needs to be the only dog in the house. She is very jealous and doesn’t like to share toys or food with other dogs.

Cats: Not much exposure

Kids: Adult home only, no young kids. She is your typical Chihuahua and bonds with her one person.

Housebroken: Not yet, about 80%, Millie HATES the cold.

Leash Trained: Not yet - she will need a home with a fenced yard - no apartments or condos and she is trained on a doggy door too!

Crate Trained: Yes

Sheds: Not Much

Barks: yes, normal barking, not excessive. 

Car Rides: She seems to be OK in the car.


Millie is very cuddly. A TOTAL SNUGGLE BUG! Her favorite spot is on a lap or snuggled up right next to you. She must be able to sleep with you at night in bed.  She is very playful with people and dogs --- although, she doesn’t like to share her toys or food with other dogs, so Millie will do best as the only dog in the home.

Millie was rescued from the highway weaving through busy traffic in Mexico. She was full of fleas and very skinny. Millie has turned into a gem. She will be the perfect only pet in the home and will keep your lap warm.


Millie was rescued in Guadalajara, Mexico and fostered in Mexico through our organization “The MexiMutt Project” (You can read more about our organization on Facebook and Instagram). Please keep in mind that our dogs are rescued off the streets or were living outside 24/7 --- so they are NOT always 100% housebroken and will need time to adjust and transition.


Adoption fee is $550 - that covers all of the vaccines (DHLPP, Rabies and Bordetella), current on flea/tick treatment, fecal testing, deworming, sterilization (spay/neuter), Heartworm-Lyme-Ehrlichia-Anaplasma Blood Test, dental cleaning (if needed), Distemper and Parvo blood test to make sure the dog is disease-free, Health Certificate, Microchip with registration, grooming before transport and the flight transport from Guadalajara, Mexico to Portland, Oregon. We will also send the dog home with a brand new collar, ID tag, leash and a small bag of the kibble.


Fill out an online adoption application here: www.BAPBR.org


*Please know that we are a 100% volunteer ran organization, with no paid employees and we work full time jobs and have our own families to care for as well. Due to the large number of applications we receive - we are not able to reply to everyone individually. If we think you are the right match for our dog, we will reach out to you and set up a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for understanding.

animal.description:
Meet Honey Toast!

Hello, we would like you to meet Honey Toast. She is a 9 yr old, 30 lb mix, although the vet said she could afford to lose 3 to 5 pounds. We do not know any of her background other than she came up from the south. Her behavior & sweetness would suggest that she was loved at one time and something unfortunate happened. You can't tell from her pictures, but she is blind. Please don't feel sad or sorry for her because she does not let that stop her. Toast just relies heavily on her other senses and does just fine. She is a happy, sweet, loving girl, who moves a bit slower due to some arthritis. Toast gets around by smelling her surroundings or follows the sound of your voice or other sounds like patting your leg. For the first few days she is going to rely on you to help her learn her new surroundings. She loves all the attention you are willing to give her. Please remember to talk to Toast as you approach her or before you touch her - it's just not fun if you pop out of nowhere and touch her without warning. Remember, she needs to hear you since she cannot see you. She will be so very happy to receive your attention. She really likes ear scratches and belly rubs. She would love to sit up on the furniture with her family, she is respectful when asking. If she is not welcome on the sofa she is happy to just curl up at your feet on a pillow or dog bed. She will kennel up if you need her to and probably a good idea if you are going to be gone for a long time to keep her safe, although she would probably just sleep all day but kenneling would give you a peace of mind that she is safe. Toast is house trained, if on a regular potty schedule. Her cues are a little hard to pick up so a regular schedule is just easier. Toast is being fostered with 5 other dogs, two her size and 3 smaller. She has yet to engage them in activity and she just leaves them alone. However, she is very willing to share a bed with them. Toast is a good eater, very food motivated, and she will try to follow her nose to other food bowls if she finishes first. She has not been around children but her calm easy going demeanor would suggest she would be fine around older more respectful kids that understand her specialness. We don't believe cats would be a problem either as she would not see them to chase them, and she's a slow mover. Her ideal forever home would be a calm clutter free environment. She can manage the two steps off the back porch with a little guidance, but since she can not see a flight of stairs it would be best to keep her clear from them so she won't fall down them. If you have a comfortable dog bed regardless of size in any room that you are in, she will find it and curl up on it just to be near you. If you have room in your heart, and time for a sweet easy going girl who has lots of love to give her new family. Please consider Toast. She is such a loving girl!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

animal.description:
Blue Bonnet is such a loving, soulful being. It doesn’t take much to fall in love with this girl and recognize that her life hasn’t been easy, and that she’s amazingly inspiring to be so
joyful! Her past was full of massive neglect, extreme over breeding and most of her life caged awaiting her next heat cycle. This beautiful being deserves a cherished home and a heart felt apology on behalf of mankind. Her resilience, loving, calm temperament, loyalty and appreciation for the simplest things,  sunshine, cuddles, kisses, car rides even just back and forth to the vet and her authentic joy of life is humbling. She is discerning at first, why wouldn’t she be, and then when she sees that a person’s intention is kind, her grateful eyes and trusting submissive invitation to rub her face and belly makes you feel so good to be recognized as earning her discerning rating as kind and trustworthy. 

She is 4 years old HW + and awaiting the next portion of her treatment. The treatments costs will be covered by the rescue. Her original X-rays show both her heart and lungs had been affected, though and her body is responding very well to the vetting and other than an occasional cough, she is thriving. 

During treatments, she will need to stay low active and luckily she truly prefers a very calm lifestyle anyway and will be very easily cooperative thru the recovery time. She absolutely loves couch cuddling with her people, loves walks, sleeping outside in the sunshine, any treats, being with the family, car rides and often appreciates the sanctuary of her crate preferably in the family room. She is great with other calm dogs and moderately tolerates the rambunctious ones. Great with all loving people, good with respectful children, wary of strangers, protective of intruders though fabulous in a crate when workers come when shown you have it covered.   She is very smart, knows sit, and stay, has a very gentle mouth, sits and waits her turn for treats while respectfully allowing other dogs to get theirs. She has no food aggression and once trust is earned, easily allows even her highest value items to easily be removed.  She is extremely responsive, wants to please , a fast learner and is a true love. A blessing to be around one so forgiving and resilient.  

She will need someone compassionate and generous who understands and loves the breed with the ability to give her the love she so badly deserves and never got until rescued. 

There’s a beautiful video about her at the below link. 

https://www.facebook.com/706989103/posts/10159099478929104/?d=n

animal.description:
How's about a handsome black cur mix or maybe a little bit of hound/mastiff in there - honestly, we have zero clue what he's made up of but goodness it's a great cocktail!!

He had what we think was a tough life before he was rescued by our friends at All 4's - he was tied up with a chain in someone's back yard. Eventually they were able to convince the owner to let him go so his vetting has been done and he's ready to start his life.

His foster mom reports he absolutely LOVES LOVES LOVES stuffed animals or ""babies"" as she calls them. He leaves the toys all over the house, she picks them up, puts them in the ""toy box"" and he then takes them out again and distributes them throughout the house.

He's ""super loving and sweet"" with her and her nieces and nephews that come to visit - he is tentative around strangers but is getting better all the time!

He is walking really well on a leash and his recall is getting really good!

Need an adopter with dog experience. Prefers smaller men.

Hope you'll consider this guy.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.


At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.




NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
MARLEY, 9 years, was brought to Babylon Animal Shelter as a stray last Oct. The only indication this weathered senior once had a home was a filthy yellow collar around his neck. Shortly after, it was learned MARLEY was a known dog who had spent most of his life on the end of a chain. The man who placed that yellow collar around his neck never came for him, which was the most fortunate act in MARLEY’S entire life. 

When we met MARLEY during our shelter outreach initiative we promised we would be back for him. Today, we made good on this and picked him up as a transfer to our #OneLuckyPup program. 

Somewhere in the euphoria of warm hugs from the incredible shelter volunteers, smiling shelter staff, elation from our team on the ground and the camaraderie of adding a new foster to our organization, a worn but robust dog wearing the gentle anxiety that comes from something unknown but decidedly good happening, became ours.

MARLEY’S unkind past included another dog, but he is not well socialized and is reactive to more dogs than not - this may be stress or he may be dog selective. He would like a home where he can age gracefully as your only pet and reverse the years of living outside, restricted to the boundaries of his chain. MARLEY has skin and dental issues we will  be addressing before he is adopted. Mostly though, MARLEY is everything you see in the video!

To adopt MARLEY within a four hour drive of Long Island visit the below link for an online application: www.mrbonesandco.org/adopt
Questions? elli@mrbonesandco.org

#AdoptMarleyMBC

animal.description:
Euro is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Euro is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~3 years 
Weight: ~42lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time to settle but overall doing well with his crate training
Dog sociability: Selective with dog pals. May be a match for some, but not all. Doesn't particularly enjoy meeting dogs on walks and may do best with slower intros. 
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Unknown
Ideal home: Euro is looking for a home in a quieter neighborhood. He is heartworm positive and will need to maintain exercise restriction for the next ~9 months, so lots of enrichment should be in his future! He is also a tripod, but that doesn't slow him down one bit!

Euro is the sweetest guy with three legs and one big heart of gold! He has the silkiest black fur that will make you want to pet him endlessly. Euro loves to be with his people and is always content to sit next to you and take in some snuggles. He hasn't really gotten the hang of toys too much yet, but he might with some more time! He very much enjoys walks where he can sniff all the things on the sidewalk and explore his neighborhood. He has been a little iffy with other dogs, and may like some but probably wouldn't want to be in a dog park environment - slower intros are more his speed. Euro is looking for an adopter that can provide lots of good mental enrichment (puzzle toys, treat balls, etc) while he needs to be kept calm these next few months as he undergoes his heartworm treatment. Euro came to us as tripod and we do not know why he's missing a limb, but this guy gets around just fine and is adaptable to many living environments. 

Euro is heartworm positive and will be undergoing treatment at our Ellis Veterinary Clinic. OTAT will cover the cost of his treatment until he is heartworm negative. For information on the heartworm treatment process, visit: onetail.org/heartworm

Euro's adoption fee is 300. He will be neutered on a future date (3/4/21) and a 50 refundable neuter deposit will be required. He is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. He will require booster vaccines at the adopter's expense. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Wraith is a beautiful 9 month old puppy. Wraith is intact but will be neutered while at his foster home. He is a very large Dutch Shepherd that is approximately 28" tall and 88 pounds. Wraith came form a breeder and was purchased by his owner who was seperated ta the time. The owner is not married and there are two other dogs in the home. Wraith gets along better with females and less dominant dogs. He is currently in his second fear period and is very afraid of new stimuli, strangers, and new places. He warms up well given about 30 minutes. 

Wraith needs an experienced owner due to his lack of socialization and training. He knows a few commands like sit and down. He walks very well on a leash. He rides very well in a car and just settles down in the back. 

Wraith lived with children in his prior home on a part time basis, however it is recommended that he go to a home with no children or only older more experienced teenagers. 

Wraith has absolutely NO ball drive. He is not recommended with cats or small dogs. 

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
Gidget and Smiley are a bonded pair of girls who will only be adopted TOGETHER. Gidget is a lively fun, little dog and these two love to play together. Smiley was raised in a hoarding situation in an outside pen with many other dogs, and was not socialized as a puppy, so she is nervous around new people. If you give her time and patience, she will come for pets and ear rubs. She is a good girl, who is quiet and very gentle, and she loves car rides. Both dogs enjoy toys and wrestling and napping together. 

Both of the girls are young adults, so an ideal home will be willing to take them for walks and have a securely fenced yard.

This pair is NOT recommended for a family with young children. 

If you are reading this, we are still accepting applications on this pet. 

Our Adoption Process:


	Meet the Adoption Criteria. Before you do anything else, make sure you meet our adoption criteria. You must be at least 21 years old. You must live within a 60-mile radius of Richardson, Texas. You must share veterinary records for all pets currently in your home and all pets owned in the last five years. All pets in the home must be spayed or neutered. If you rent your home, you must provide verification that pets are allowed on the property. You must be willing to be interviewed by an adoption counselor and you must undergo an in person or virtual home visit from an RHS representative.
	Complete Application. https://www.richardsonhumanesociety.org/adopt/
	Phone Interview. Compatible applicants will be forwarded to a counselor who will contact the applicant for a phone interview.
	Home Visit. If all the steps above are completed satisfactorily, we will set up a visit where you can meet the pet you are interested in. We will try to include the foster parent so you can learn more about how the pet is in a home environment.
	Complete Adoption. If all feel it is a good match, we will schedule the adoption at your home or an off-site location. The applicant will need to complete the adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fee is $250 for adult dogs, $300 for puppies (under 1 year) and $125 for cats. Discounts are available for senior-aged pets.

animal.description:
Bonita would like you to know one thing... giving birth is tough. Giving birth in the back of a moving vehicle is WAY tough! Sweet Bonita found herself pregnant and at her wit's end in an overcrowded Oklahoma shelter. Pulled for rescue and en route to Muddy Paws, Bonita settled in for her long ride to freedom. Now, whether it was the vibration of the vehicle or the relaxation of rescue we'll never know... Either way, Bonita decided it was as good a time as any to bring her 11 little surprises into the world! This set off a change of plans as the transport had to turn around and head back to Oklahoma so that Bonita and her babies could ALL be deemed healthy and ready for travel. Whew! After all that, Bonita and family are finally here, safe and cozy in a foster home. Bonita is rockin' the new mom life and we'll have more updates about her over the coming weeks! *Please note: We are currently accepting applications for Bonita but she will not be available for physical adoption until she is finished caring for her pups.

The suggested adoption donation for Bonita is $400. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes. 

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months. 

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Meet Pooky! Pooky is a healthy 17 lbs. Havanese. He is 10 month old happy puppy that loves to play and cuddle.  Pooky has puppy energy and is at the perfect age to begin obedience training.  He is very busy and would do best with another dog with whom to play. 
He is new to the rescue and his profile will be updated as we get to know him better!
If you’d like to meet Pooky, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestierescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 
Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 
Pooky’s adoption fee is $400 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.
We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 
We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human.
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

Shadow, his mom, and his siblings were all picked up as strays and taken to a high kill shelter in Alabama.  These great dogs were never reclaimed.  The shelter staff loved them because all of them were so sweet and calm.  We saw a video of them and we had to go and save them!   

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.COMING SOON! We are looking for a foster or forever home for this beautiful girl named Noel before she gets to WNY!

Noel came into a shelter down South as a stray. They knew no one would dare try to reclaim her, given her conditions. They would be instantly charged with animal cruelty. Their very first instinct was bait dog. Noel had bite marks all over her head and legs. Her teeth are worn down, she's been bred over and over and she's emaciated. But really we have no idea Noel's story or how she ended up at the shelter.

She's clearly had a really rough life. She loves people and is very sweet. But just doesn't like other dogs. Can we blame her? She's never known kindness.

Are you the one to give her the happily ever after she deserves? Please apply online today!

** Thank-you Joyce for your Sponsorship donation for Noel!! Adoption donation includes Spay/Neuter, UTD on Vaccinations, deworming, and flea treatment.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ ENTIRE DESCRIPTION BEFORE INQUIRING

Include your location when you email us for an application. Emails that don't include your location may not receive a response. 

If you send more than one email you will not receive a response. It clogs our inbox up and slows down our response time.

Meet Frisco. This cute 1-2 year od, little 10lb fluffy boy had been running loose and was trapped by a good citizen.  While Frisco is adorable, he does have some behavioral challenges.  His most serious challenge is an adversion to strangers and he will bark, chase and display ankle biter tendencies.   He also is territorial and has barrier reactivity which may subside since he is now neutered. Frisco's good qualities are that he does warm up quickly when taken out of his territory and once he gets to know you, he will be your protector.  He also has been good with other dogs and cats as well.  Frisco has been neutered, vaccinated, tested negative for heartworm, dewormed, microchipped, on flea and tick preventative and heartworm preventative.  He is now available for adoption to a very special quiet, low traffic home with no children and someone that is willing to set him up for success. Frisco is leash trained, crate trained and working on potty training.

A home check is required. Yolo County adopters preferred, but will consider other locations. If you are more than 100 miles away from Yolo County please be aware that there may be a small additional expense associated with travel cost. 

If you are interested in adopting Frisco, email us and we will send you an adoption application. (include your location in the email) The adoption fee for Frisco is $250. 

*Vetting includes: Neuter/spay, microchip, age appropriate vaccinations, deworming, heartworm test, flea preventative, heart worm preventative (including the remainder of their 6-month supply), and any other necessary vet care.

animal.description:
Fonteyn was rescued from under a car.  She danced her way into the rescuer's heart, but doesn't care for his dogs, so is waiting for God to send her forever family.

With a guesstimated birthday in Jan. 2020, Fonteyn weighs about 15 lb.  Although she's initially timid, once she attaches herself to her person she wants to be where they are.  

Fonteyn would prefer to be an only dog.  She doesn't mind dogs her size, but doesn't like to share her people (resource guarding).  She'll growl at her favorite doggy friends if they come too close when she's on her person's lap.  

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

When you first meet DONOVAN, he melts your heart with those gorgeous brown and blue eyes and his warm, friendly demeanor. He will walk right up to you with his tail wagging and lean in close for some hands-on attention. He loves being loved! Just 2.5 years old and about 60lbs, this sweet, friendly lab mix would do best in a home where someone is home most of the day, i.e. a guardian who has a home office or is semi-retired, etc. He needs at least one friendly, low/medium energy canine companion to help with confidence building and learning the ropes, together with a fenced-in yard where they can play or chillax and enjoy the sights and sounds of the seasons.

His guardian describes him as follows: "Donovan is just an awesome, loveable, and super sweet boy who is going to be someone's Furever Heart Dog. He's snuggly and affectionate and loves his people. Donovan wouldn't make a good jogging or high intensity hiking buddy. He is generally a mellow fellow but enjoys a good ball game outdoors and a casual walk. Generally a quiet pup, he may be talkative when he wants to play ball with you. He'll lay down with a ball and beckon you to come and throw it for him to chase. Once he gets it, more often than not, he'll lay down and bark to me to come get the ball and throw it again. He may be fine with cats since when he met them at boarding last week, he was a scaredy cat. AND he loves meeting new people. The moment he spots someone new, he starts wiggling his butt and wagging his tail and working his way toward them to say hello and share a moment."

DONOVAN hasn't received much training in his life. His foster has been working on some basic commands and where to go potty, and he's doing great. He is treat and praise motivated and would benefit from some positive reinforcement training and mental enrichment activities. He isn't crate trained and doesn't like it at all. He may do best in a gated, dog friendly area when left unsupervised.

DONOVAN is neutered and up to date on age-appropriate shots. His adoption fee is $425. which includes a spay/neuter fee. Please note that training is highly recommended for all young dogs.

As with all rescue animals, breed determination cannot be validated without genetic testing. Visit WWW.LULUSRESCUE.ORG for an overview of Lulu's Rescue adoption process and/or to request an adoption application.

Thanks for adopting and saving a life!

animal.description:
MEET CORKY! He is a little Italian Greyhound mix. Corky is only 2 years old and weighs 6.5 pounds. Corky is being fostered in Titusville, FL.
Due to Covid-19 all dogs fostered in the state of Florida must be adopted within the State of Florida.


UPDATED BIO 01/10/2021: Who would have thought that an adorable, tiny little Italian Greyhound Mix would be in a Yorkie rescue group? When you know there is a shelter dog that needs you, one who needs to be out of the shelter and in a quiet, safe place, there is no question that our hearts would open up to little Corky and make him our first United Yorkie Rescue Italian Greyhound Mix rescue boy.

Corky was found by Animal Control wandering the streets back in late December no microchip was found. He was posted on the shelter website and he waited and waited for his family to come find him and take him home. No one came for him. This tiny dog didn't belong in a shelter with so many big loud dogs. Finally, the shelter was ready to put him up for adoption, then their vet resigned and there was no one to neuter Corky. The shelter knew the only place for him was a rescue and so this little guy became a United Yorkie Rescue dog.

Corky has only been in his foster home for several days, but that is long enough for his foster family to know that he is the sweetest little boy and they already adore him. He yearns to be around his new foster family and loves to be held and cuddled and snuggled under the covers at night. Corky likes to talk to his family - not a bark or whine - but something in between. He is most likely letting them know how much he appreciates being rescued and finding a temporary loving family to show him that he is safe and that he will never ever end up in a shelter again. His foster family is working with him on reinforcing house-training. He is young and smart and will catch on quickly.

Corky didn't take long to make himself right at home. He hopped right into the bed as if that's what he is supposed to do, and proceeded to sit in a chair at the dinner table. Why not? Of course, this isn't proper puppy protocol, and he is learning house manners and catching on quickly. He thought when he saw one of the resident chickens in the yard that he was supposed to chase it, but that's a no-no lol! The Italian Greyhound is classified as a sight hound, so it's best that Corky's forever family only have perhaps one other dog. Cats, rabbits, etc. would probably not be a good idea. Corky prefers the company of the humans in the home over the other dogs in the home, so he would also be fine as an only doggie.

Because Corky really loves attention from his foster family, it would be nice for him to have a home with at least one stay-at-home parent. Italian Greyhounds are highly social dogs and love attention from their family. Corky still needs to be neutered and have some deciduous baby teeth pulled, and once that is done, he will be ready for his forever home. There is so much more to learn about this sweet little boy, so come back soon to learn more about him.

PLEASE NOTE: Due to Corky's small size, he needs an adult only home or a home with children over the age of 13. Keep in mind Corky is very young and since he has already lost one family, his forever family needs to be one that will be with him for his expected life span of 15 years or more.

animal.description: Meet Blue... the most Will Ferrell of dogs. He embodies Will from the movies Elf to Step Brothers. His goofy personality is so fun and derpy. He wants everyone to be his friend. At 65lbs and 2 years old Blue doesn't have many secrets in life, he lays all of his feelings out on the table. From his dying cow impersonating (shared walls are not a great idea) to his clumsy antics, Blue is an awesome dog that just needs some fine tuning (Such as maybe Ricky Bobby). He needs some work in the areas of knocking him down a peg... in his words "I'm kind of a big deal" he's got a giant head (literally and figuratively) and wants all the attentions. He also talks back but doesn't win most arguments. If he has experienced something unfavorable to him, he will tell you all about it. He is just so smooshy and lovable, full of wrinkles and fun. He's pretty much a overgrown puppy learning how to use his paws and mouth gently. His foster mom calls him an idiot, but Buddy the Elf would call him a Cotton Headed Ninny Muggins. He is great with all dogs, a little scared of cats and with humans, he's never met one he didn't like, however tiny human are probably not a good idea because he has no idea where his body his at and he sits where he pleases. Even if that is on their head. This boy deserves some adventures! Give him a try - you will not be disappointed. Blue's adoption fee is $350 which covers his neuter, vaccinations, microchip and any additional medical care he may have needed while in the rescues care. We are a foster based rescue, we do not house dogs at a facility. Age and breed, are NLR's best guess as we often don't know who or what mom and dad are. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website www.northernlakesrescue.org

animal.description:
**Please Note: This is a courtesy post for another rescue; different adoption fees/policy apply

Meet Max,

This sweet doggie has been waiting in boarding for a long time for his forever home.! It's time for Max to have his very own home so he can run around. He has gone through some awesome training, he knows lots of commands plus so much more, and the rescue will continue his training for life for FREE....

Why have I not found a family? I'm about 2-3 years old, and I am a quick learner (especially if you have treats!) I don't react to the dogs around me and I'm already neutered, and up-to-date on shots. I love water, toys, car rides, puppacinos, and just being a dog. However, I feel sad, depressed, and lonely each day and night when people leave and I'm once again in my kennel alone with nothing to do. This Phoenix heat is terrible and all I want is to have a home with air conditioning, love, a secure yard, lots of toys, yummy treats, and someone who will spend time with me. I get overexcited sometimes, I will feel much more secure, confident, calm, and will be your loyal companion. I told you I am a quick learner, so much that my best friend Bob is teaching me to dance!

He's friendly and likes most dogs but he needs to go to a home with no other pets. He will do best as an ONLY DOG at this time........ Max is great with older children since he gets excited at time 12+ years, Even though he's a really good boy, Max is always eager to learn more. A comfy bed, new bowls and a bag of treats will accompany Max to his new home. And of course he'll bring along his favorite toy.

Max would love to have his own yard and family to love. No apartments or Condo's/townhomes

Max need to have a home with a backyard, he likes to run around and play with secure fencing.

Contact 480-359-7109 for more information

For more information or to meet this pet, please complete an application or send email to info@underdogaz.com

If you're reading this via a pet-search site, please view this pet's page

at www.UnderdogAZ.com/animals

for more photos and details.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Farlo is a 50-pound male mixed breed (likely a lab/pit/boxer) born into rescue in November 2019 after his Mom was rescued in North Carolina. Gorgeous Farlo, with his beautiful markings, is good with people, and, after a slow introduction, other dogs and even cats, although he would do best with older children. Farlo is housebroken, he loves riding in the car and walks well on a leash. He enjoys playing with other dogs and with his toys, especially his stuffies! Farlo has low vision, but it doesn't stop him from any adventures or activities. Farlo's forever home will be in the suburbs with an experienced owner who will continue to provide him with the structure and exercise he needs to be his very best self. To bring this happy, stunning boy into your life, please apply online at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description:
Name: Bella
Suspected Breed: Lab/Pointer Mix
Approximate Age: 4 years old
Approximate Weight: 61 lbs
Observations with Dogs: Reactive on leash, but has done well with other dogs with proper intro
Observations with Cats: Too interested in kitties 
Observations with Kids: Best in a home without children
Currently Living at: DC-area foster home

See Bella's adoption video here: https://youtu.be/h7OOGYp-wv0

Please meet our beautiful Bella! She is loyal, sweet, and playful, and she has so much love to give. Even though she is 60 pounds, she still thinks of herself as a lap dog. She loves belly rubs and generally any kind of scratches. 

Because of her anxiety and reactivity, Bella needs a calm home without children. This means that if you have children under the age of 15, frequently have children in your home, or are planning on having children, she is probably not the dog for you. She also needs slow introductions to visitors, whatever their age.

She's smart and eager to please, which makes her highly trainable. Bella is a very energetic dog, so she needs an adopter who either is active and can take her running or can commit to lots of play. If her adopter is not a runner, she'll need a fenced-in yard to play with her adopter to supplement daily long walks.

Bella does beautifully in the home when there is no chaos and she has had plenty of exercise. She thrives on routine and predictability. In the right home with plenty of exercise, Bella is a calm girl who loves to snuggle. She can live in the city with someone who is willing and able to work with her on-leash reactivity, but she would also do very well in a more suburban or rural area. Bella has previously done well both in rural areas and in urban areas with appropriate training.

Bella is doing well in her foster home and is very affectionate. Her foster reports that she loves to keep him company on her sofa while he works and that when she's happy, her tail goes in circles like a propeller. Bella has done well in the crate with positive reinforcement and has not had any accidents in her foster homes. She is a highly intelligent dog and enjoys puzzle toys. 

Bella is working with her foster on leash reactivity. While she likes other dogs with proper introduction and has been fostered with other canines in the home, she gets scared and nervous when she sees other dogs on a leash. When that happens, she sometimes pulls on her leash, whines, or barks. Right now we are taking Bella on walks in the early morning and later at night in order to avoid other dogs until she is more comfortable. We also have enlisted the help of a top area trainer who specializes in reactivity. With patience and positive reinforcement, she has already improved dramatically.

While she would do fine as an only dog, Bella really likes to play with other dogs that she knows and likes. She needs to be properly introduced to other dogs and doesn't take to all dogs she meets. If you have a dog who could use a companion to wear them out, Bella may be the dog for you!

Bella needs an adopter who is willing to consistently help her cope with fears, which she is exhibiting less and less but will always need some management. We recommend additional work with a trainer for her with her adopter, since training is about teaching the human as much as it is about teaching the dog! A class also has the benefit of building a closer bond between dog and human. We want to ensure her forever family continues to reinforce the positive behaviors and helps Bella continue to build confidence.

Bella requires a diet free of chicken, and she takes medication to manage her allergies. She has suffered from persistent ear infections and allergies. We have figured out the right combination of diet, medication, and ear maintenance, and it has really helped her disposition.

Like most shelter dogs, Bella may need a refresher on house training and crate training. We ask all of DC PAWS' fosters to work on both house and crate training with their foster dog. 

The adoption fee for this dog is $350. If you are interested in adopting Bella, please submit an adoption application at http://dcpawsrescue.org/adoption-info/.ABOUT US & IMPORTANT DISCLOSURES:

Please note that you must use our official adoption application in order to be considered for adoption. Applying through other sites (i.e., Petfinder) will not work. The following are our applications:

Dog application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=1
Cat application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=6

DC PAWS Rescue does our best to provide accurate and complete information about our adoptable animals. Please note that we cannot make any guarantees about age or breed; we rely upon our rescue partners and their veterinarians to make those assessments. We also cannot make any guarantees about housebreaking and animal temperament, as animals can behave differently through transition and in different environments.

Our shelter partners provide a basic vet screening for each animal we rescue, which includes necessary vaccinations, deworming, microchipping, and spay/neuter (unless the animal is too young or otherwise deemed by the vet to not be a good candidate for surgery). Please note that this is not a comprehensive medical exam and as such, may not identify any and all medical issues, though our goal is to flag any obvious health issues through the basic vet screening. We share all medical records with adopters and are completely transparent about any known issues prior to adoption finalization. 

ABOUT DC PAWS RESCUE

Our rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based dog and cat rescue in the DC area. We rescue locally from Prince Georges County, MD, and from rural shelters in the south (presently Pickens County, Anderson County, and Greenville County in SC, and Raleigh County, WV).

We partner with a local rescuer in Pickens County, SC, who saves adoptable cats and dogs from the three area shelters. For the animals in this rural area, rescue is a critical lifeline, and often the only lifeline. Our rescue partner not only works with DC PAWS to save as many dogs and cats as possible, but she has also established a successful spay/neuter program in the community to decrease the number of homeless and unwanted animals over the long term.

FOSTER AN ANIMAL IN NEED

Fosters make it possible for DC PAWS to save and care for homeless, neglected and abandoned animals! To learn about fostering dogs or cats for DC PAWS Rescue, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/volunteer/fostering/foster-application

SPONSOR AN ANIMAL IN NEED

For any of our animals! Sponsors help us provide critical medical care, food, boarding, and other support for animals facing euthanasia. Individuals who sponsor a dog or cat receive special recognition on the animal's profile. Sponsorships can also be made in honor or memory of a loved one, and you may designate to whom DC PAWS Rescue should provide notice of your gift. Sponsorship levels of $250 and $150 include ""naming rights"" for a future dog or cat (respectively) that we rescue.

To learn more about sponsorship, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/donate/

animal.description:
This is Shilo. He was surrendered to us by a woman that could not take care of him. The story is, the womans husky escaped and returned pregnant. Shilo was the most timid of the puppies and apparently the woman was not able to adopt him out and could no longer care for him. This is very disturbing to us as he is only 7 weeks old and puppies should not be adopted out until 8 weeks. We had no choice but to take him in early considering the other siblings fate.We know that he is very, very shy. Cannot look at you in the eyes and very scared at first. We are still monitoring his behavior to see how long before he will come out of his shell. He will be available for adoption on Feb. 10th. By then, we will have a good idea of how his personality is. We can start reviewing applications in the meantime.
